\left(\mathbf{Y} \times_{d} \mathbf{U}\right)_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{n}}:=\sum_{j=1}^{R_{d}} U_{i_{d}, j} Y_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{d-1}, j, i_{d+1}, \ldots, i_{n}}, \quad \forall i_{k} \in\left[R_{k}\right](k \neq d), i_{d} \in[p]
$$

We now restrict attention to the three-way tensors. Let $\widetilde{\mathbf{I}} \in \mathbb{R}^{R \times R \times R}$ denote the three-way tensor with ones along its super-diagonal and zeros elsewhere such that its entry $\widetilde{I}_{i_{1}, i_{2}, i_{3}}=1_{i_{1}=i_{2}=i_{3}}$ for all $i_{1}, i_{2}, i_{3} \in[R]$. For matrices $\mathbf{U}_{1} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{1} \times R}, \mathbf{U}_{2} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{2} \times R}, \mathbf{U}_{3} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{3} \times R}$, we define

$$
\left\llbracket \mathbf{U}_{1}, \mathbf{U}_{2}, \mathbf{U}_{3} \rrbracket:=\widetilde{\mathbf{I}} \times{ }_{1} \mathbf{U}_{1} \times{ }_{2} \mathbf{U}_{2} \times{ }_{3} \mathbf{U}_{3}\right.
$$

which is a three-way tensor of dimensions $p_{1} \times p_{2} \times p_{3}$. Given $\mathbf{Y} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{1} \times p_{2} \times p_{3}}$ and $R$, finding these matrices $\mathbf{U}_{1}, \mathbf{U}_{2}, \mathbf{U}_{3}$ such that $\mathbf{Y}=\llbracket \mathbf{U}_{1}, \mathbf{U}_{2}, \mathbf{U}_{3} \rrbracket$ is known as the $C P$ decomposition of rank $R$ (Kolda and Bader, 2009).

For a matrix $\mathbf{A}$, we let its Kruskal rank, denoted by $\operatorname{rank}_{K}(\mathbf{A})$, be the maximal number $k$ such that any $k$ columns of $\mathbf{A}$ are linearly independent. In the following Theorem B.1, we state the seminal result of Kruskal (1977) that provides a condition under which the uniqueness of CP decomposition of rank $R$ is guaranteed up to column rescaling and permutation.

Theorem B. 1 (Kruskal's Theorem). Let $\mathbf{U}_{1} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{1} \times R}, \mathbf{U}_{2} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{2} \times R}, \mathbf{U}_{3} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{3} \times R}$ be matrices satisfying the condition

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\mathbf{U}_{1}\right)+\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\mathbf{U}_{2}\right)+\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\mathbf{U}_{3}\right) \geq 2 R+2
$$

Then for any matrices $\widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{1} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{1} \times R}, \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{2} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{2} \times R}, \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{3} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{3} \times R}$ such that

$$
\left\llbracket \mathbf{U}_{1}, \mathbf{U}_{2}, \mathbf{U}_{3} \rrbracket=\llbracket \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{2}, \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{3} \rrbracket\right.
$$

there exist diagonal matrices $\mathbf{Q}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{2}, \mathbf{Q}_{3} \in \mathbb{R}^{R \times R}$ satisfying $\mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{Q}_{2} \mathbf{Q}_{3}=\mathbf{I}$ and a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{R \times R}$ such that

$$
\widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{1}=\mathbf{U}_{1} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{2}=\mathbf{U}_{2} \mathbf{Q}_{2} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{U}}_{3}=\mathbf{U}_{3} \mathbf{Q}_{3} \mathbf{P}
$$

In simple terms, if a three-way tensor admits a CP decomposition $\llbracket \mathbf{U}_{1}, \mathbf{U}_{2}, \mathbf{U}_{3} \rrbracket$ of rank $R$, with the Kruskal ranks of $\mathbf{U}_{1}, \mathbf{U}_{2}, \mathbf{U}_{3}$ summing to be $\geq 2 R+2$, then such a CP decomposition of rank $R$ is unique up to column rescaling and permutation of $\mathbf{U}_{i}$ 's. Proofs of Theorem B. 1 can be found in Kruskal (1977) and Rhodes (2010).

# B. 2 Proof of Theorem 3.4 

Recall that $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ denotes the collection of all $p_{k} \times p_{k}$ adjacency matrices. The cardinality of $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ is $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|=2^{\frac{p_{k}\left(p_{k}-1\right)}{2}}$ due to the symmetry and the all-ones diagonal. We distinguish the notations Law and $\mathbb{P}$. For instance, $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ denotes the categorical distribution of $\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$ over $\mathcal{X}_{k}$, whereas $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ denotes the probability for a specific $\mathbf{X}_{k} \in \mathcal{X}_{k}$ under this distribution.

We let $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ be an arbitrary bijective map from $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ to the set of integers $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|\right]=\left\{1,2, \ldots,\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|\right\}$. We characterize the marginal distribution $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ through a $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|$-dimensional probability vector $\mathbf{v}_{k} \in \mathcal{S}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|-1}$, such that

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)=v_{k, \mathcal{X}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right)} \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k} \in \mathcal{X}_{k}
$$

for $v_{k, i}$ denoting the $i$ th entry of $\mathbf{v}_{k}$. Similarly, for $X_{k, i, j}$ denoting the $(i, j)$ th entry in $\mathbf{X}_{k}$, we characterize its conditional distribution $\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ through a $\left(2 \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right)$-dimensional matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k,(i, j)}$, such that

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}=1_{\ell=1} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)=\Lambda_{k,(i, j), \ell, \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)} \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}, \ell \in\{1,2\}
$$

for $\Lambda_{k,(i, j), \ell, r}$ denoting the $(\ell, r)$ th entry of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k,(i, j)}$. That is, the first row of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k, i, j}$ represents the probabilities of $X_{k, i, j}=1$, the second row represents the probabilities of $X_{k, i, j}=0$, and the $r$ th column represents conditioning on $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(r)$. Recall that $\langle p\rangle:=\{(i, j): 1 \leq i<j \leq p\}$ denotes the collection of all pairs of distinct indices in $[p]$. By taking Khatri-Rao product (Kolda and Bader, 2009) of the matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k,(i, j)}$ over all $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, we obtain the $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ matrix

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}:=\odot_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k,(i, j)}
$$

which fully characterizes the conditional distribution $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ due to the conditional independence of entries in $\mathbf{X}_{k}$. Note that the order of pairs $(i, j)$ 's in $\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ when taking the KhatriRao product does not matter in our proof.

Noticing that

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)=\sum_{\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}} \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)
$$

by viewing each $\mathbf{v}_{k}$ as a column vector, for all $k \in[K]$ we have

$$
\mathbf{v}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}
$$

Since $\mathbf{v}_{k}$ and each column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ are probability vectors, they satisfy the conditions $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=1$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=\mathbf{1}$. In the following lemma, we show that among the probability vectors and matrices satisfying these conditions, $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ can be uniquely recovered from their product $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ up to shuffles of columns in $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and entries in $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$.

Lemma B.2. Let parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and layer $k \in[K]$. For any matrix $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ and vector $\widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times 1}$ satisfying

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}=\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k} \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=1, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=\mathbf{1}
$$

there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ such that

$$
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}=\mathbf{P}^{\top} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}
$$

The proof of Lemma B. 2 is based on transforming $\mathbf{v}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ into a three-way tensor and viewing $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ as a realization of its CP decomposition. The uniqueness of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ follows from Theorem B. 1 after showing the condition on the Kruskal ranks to hold. Similar proof techniques can be found in Gu and Dunson (2023) for their Proposition 2. We provide the proof of Lemma B. 2 in Section B.3.

Given the vector $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$, Lemma B. 2 states that the choice of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ are unique up to shuffles of columns/entries. Importantly, there are many more ways to shuffle the columns in $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and entries in $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ than to permute the columns of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and the rows and columns of $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$. The former corresponds to permutations over $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, whereas the latter corresponds to permutations over the $p_{k-1}$ nodes in the $(k-1)$ th layer of our Bayesian network. Given a shuffled probability vector $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ and matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ from Lemma B.2, we further want to know the $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}$ that each entry of $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ and each column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ corresponds to in (B.2) and (B.3). That is, we want to recover the bijective map $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. The following lemma establishes that $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ can be uniquely recovered from a column shuffled $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ up to permutations over the $p_{k-1}$ nodes.

Lemma B.3. Let parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and layer $k \in[K]$. For any two bijective maps $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}$ from $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$, if for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x), \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}^{-1}(x), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

then there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ such that for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$,

$$
\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}^{-1}(x)=\mathbf{P} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x) \mathbf{P}^{\top}
$$

Lemma B. 3 states that, for any two bijective maps $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}$ with possibly different model parameters, if they lead to the same probability matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$, then the adjacency matrices $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}=$ $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x)$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}=\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}^{-1}(x)$ corresponding to the $x$ th column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ must be identical up to node permutations. This implies that, given a column shuffled $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ with model parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ unknown, we can uniquely recover the bijective map $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ up to node permutations. The proof is provided in Section B.3.

After recovering $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ from the probability matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$, we know everything of the conditional distribution $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$. It then remains to recover the model parameters $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$ from this conditional distribution. The following lemma shows that the recovery of $\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$ is unique for $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ within the parameter space $\mathbf{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$, with proof provided in Section B.3.

Lemma B.4. Let parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and layer $k \in[K]$. If for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

then

$$
\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}=\mathbf{A}_{k}, \quad \widetilde{C}_{k}=C_{k}, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}
$$

Lemmas B.2, B.3, and B. 4 together provide a three-step procedure for recovering the parameters $\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$ and the probability vector $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ from $\mathbf{v}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$. We now use an induction argument for $k=K, K-1, \ldots, 1$ to sequentially recover all parameters $\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$ from the marginal distribution $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{K} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ (or equivalently from the vector $\mathbf{v}_{K}$ ) and prove Theorem 3.4.

Proof of Theorem 3.4. We let parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and pick an arbitrary $(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$, then by definition (3.2),

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{K} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{K} \mid \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right)
$$

We prove by induction for $k \in[K]$ in descending order. Let $k \in[K], \mathbf{P}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k} \times p_{k}}$ be a permutation matrix, and $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ be a bijective map from $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|\right]$. We also fix an arbitrary bijective map $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ from $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$. We let $\mathcal{N}_{k}$ be the permutation map on the integers $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|\right]$ such that for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|\right]$,

$$
\left(\mathcal{X}_{k}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{N}_{k}\right)(x):=\mathbf{P}_{k} \mathcal{X}_{k}^{-1}(x) \mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top}
$$

Accordingly, we let $\mathbf{N}_{k}$ denote the permutation matrix corresponding to $\mathcal{N}_{k}$, such that

$$
\left(\begin{array}{lll}
1 & 2 & \cdots \\
\left.\mathcal{X}_{k}\right]
\end{array}\right) \mathbf{N}_{k}=\left(\mathcal{N}_{k}(1) \mathcal{N}_{k}(2) \cdots \mathcal{N}_{k}\left(\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|\right)\right)
$$

Similar to (B.2), (B.3), and (B.4), we define the probability vectors $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}, \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{S}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|-1}$ to characterize the marginal distributions $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ and $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{A}}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right)$ such that their entries satisfy

$$
v_{k-1, \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right), \quad \tilde{v}_{k-1, \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{A}}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right)
$$

for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$; we define the probability matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ to characterize the conditional distributions $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ and $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \tilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)$ such that their entries satisfy

$$
\Lambda_{k, \mathcal{X}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right), \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right), \quad \tilde{\Lambda}_{k, \mathcal{X}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right), \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \tilde{\mathbf{A}}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right)
$$

for all $\mathbf{X}_{k} \in \mathcal{X}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$; and we define the probability vectors $\mathbf{v}_{k}, \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k} \in \mathcal{S}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right|-1}$ to characterize the marginal distributions $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ and $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{A}}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right)$ such that their entries satisfy

$$
v_{k, \mathcal{X}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right)}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right), \quad \tilde{v}_{k, \mathcal{X}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right)}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{A}}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right)
$$

for all $\mathbf{X}_{k} \in \mathcal{X}_{k}$. Similar to (B.5), we have

$$
\mathbf{v}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}, \quad \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k}=\tilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k} \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}
$$

To do the induction, we suppose for layer $k$ that $\mathbf{v}_{k}=\mathbf{N}_{k}^{\top} \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k}$. By Lemma B.2, there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{N}_{k-1} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ such that

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}=\mathbf{N}_{k}^{\top} \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k} \mathbf{N}_{k-1}, \quad \mathbf{v}_{k-1}=\mathbf{N}_{k-1}^{\top} \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}
$$

We let $\mathcal{N}_{k-1}$ denote the permutation map on $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$ corresponding to the permutation matrix $\mathbf{N}_{k-1}$, such that

$$
\left(\begin{array}{lll}
1 & 2 & \cdots \\
\left.\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right]
\end{array}\right) \mathbf{N}_{k-1}=\left(\mathcal{N}_{k-1}(1) \mathcal{N}_{k-1}(2) \cdots \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\left(\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right)\right)
$$

For simplicity, we slightly abuse notation and also let $\mathcal{N}_{k-1}$ denote the permutation map $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ$ $\mathcal{N}_{k-1} \circ \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ and $\mathcal{N}_{k}$ denote the permutation map $\mathcal{X}_{k}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{N}_{k} \circ \mathcal{X}_{k}$ on $\mathcal{X}_{k}$. Then (B.8) implies, for all $\mathbf{X}_{k} \in \mathcal{X}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$,

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathcal{N}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right) \mid \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \tilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

By definition of $\mathcal{N}_{k}$ in (B.7) and our model formulation in (2.5) and (2.6), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathcal{N}_{k}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\right) \mid \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \tilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right) & =\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{P}_{k} \mathbf{X}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top} \mid \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \tilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right) \\
& =\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top} \tilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which together with (B.9) gives for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x), \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\right)(x), \mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top} \tilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \tilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

By Lemma B.3, there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$, such that for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$,

$$
\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{N}_{k-1}\right)(x)=\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x) \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}
$$

This implies, for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$,

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}, \mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

Using our model formulation in (2.5), for each $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \\
= & \frac{\exp \left(X_{k, i, j}\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)} \\
= & \frac{\exp \left(X_{k, i, j}\left(C_{k}+\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right)\left(\left(\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right) *\left(\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right)\right)\left(\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right)\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right)\left(\left(\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right) *\left(\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right)\right)\left(\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right)} \\
= & \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{P}_{k-1} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}, \mathbf{A}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top},\left\{C_{k}, \mathbf{P}_{k-1} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right\}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Combined with (B.11), we obtain for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top},\left\{C_{k}, \mathbf{P}_{k-1} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}\right\}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

By Lemma B.4, this implies

$$
\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}=\mathbf{P}_{k} \mathbf{A}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}, \quad \widetilde{C}_{k}=C_{k}, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k}=\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}
$$

The induction passes on from layer $k$ to layer $k-1$, since $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}=\mathbf{N}_{k-1}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}$ follows from (B.8) and the permutation matrix $\mathbf{N}_{k-1}$ satisfies (B.10). It remains to show that the induction can start at layer $k=K$. We recall from (3.1) that we have specified $\mathbf{P}_{K}:=\mathbf{I}_{p_{K}}$. For the permutation matrix $\mathbf{N}_{K}:=\mathbf{I}_{\left|\mathcal{X}_{K}\right|}$ and the permutation map $\mathcal{N}_{K}:=\operatorname{Id}_{\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{K}\right|\right]}$ being the identity map, we find that

$$
\left(\mathcal{X}_{K}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{N}_{K}\right)(x)=\mathbf{P}_{K} \mathcal{X}_{K}^{-1}(x) \mathbf{P}_{K}^{\top}
$$

holds for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{K}\right|\right]$ and (B.6) is equivalent to

$$
\mathbf{v}_{K}=\widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{K}=\mathbf{N}_{K}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{K}
$$

This shows that the induction holds for $k=K$. Therefore, through induction we have shown that (B.12) holds for all $k \in[K]$. Additionally, we have $\mathbf{v}_{0}=\mathbf{N}_{0}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{0}$ for $\mathbf{N}_{0}$ and its associated $\mathcal{N}_{0}$ satisfying (B.10) with $k=1$, which implies

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right)=v_{0, \mathcal{X}_{0}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}\right)}=\widetilde{v}_{0,\left(\mathcal{N}_{0} \circ \mathcal{X}_{0}\right)\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}\right)}=\widetilde{v}_{0,\left(\mathcal{X}_{0}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{N}_{0}\right)\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}\right)}=\widetilde{v}_{0, \mathbf{P}_{0} \mathbf{X}_{0} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top}}=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{P}_{0} \mathbf{X}_{0} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mid \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\nu}}\right)
$$

All above results together establish that $(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$. This suggests

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \supset \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})
$$

for all $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$. Since by definition $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subset \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ holds, we have proven that our model with parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ is strictly identifiable.

# B. 3 Proof of Auxiliary Lemmas for Theorem 3.4 

Proof of Lemma B.2. Recalling the definition of parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{1}$ in (3.4), the matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ satisfies the blockwise condition

$$
\mathbf{P}_{k} \mathbf{A}_{k}=\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}} \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}} \mathbf{B}_{k}\right)^{\top}
$$

for $\mathbf{P}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k} \times p_{k}}$ a permutation matrix and $\mathbf{B}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times\left(p_{k}-2 p_{k-1}\right)}$ an arbitrary matrix. Without loss of generality, we can let $\mathbf{P}_{k}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k}}$. For a general layer $k$, the only probability vector and matrix involved in Lemma B. 2 are $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$, so we abbreviate them by $\mathbf{v}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}$ for notational simplicity. Similarly, we abbreviate $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k}$ by $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}, \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}$ by $\widetilde{\mathbf{v}}$, and the matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k,(i, j)}$ defined in (B.3) by $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}$.

We define four sets of index pairs in $\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{I}_{1}:=\left\{(i, j): 1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k-1}\right\} \\
& \mathcal{I}_{2}:=\left\{(i, j): p_{k-1}+1 \leq i<j \leq 2 p_{k-1}\right\} \\
& \mathcal{I}_{3}:=\left\{(i, j): 1 \leq i \leq p_{k-1}, p_{k-1}+1 \leq j \leq 2 p_{k-1}\right\} \\
& \mathcal{I}_{4}:=\left\{(i, j): 2 p_{k-1}+1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

such that together they form a partition of $\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$. This partition of $\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ corresponds to a partition of the upper-triangular off-diagonal entries of the adjacency matrix $\mathbf{X}_{k}$ into four blocks. Similar to (B.4), we characterize the conditional distributions of each block as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}:=\odot_{(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{1}} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|} \\
& \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}:=\odot_{(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{2}} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|} \\
& \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]}:=\odot_{(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{3}} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)} \in \mathbb{R}^{2^{p_{k-1}^{2}} \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|} \\
& \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}:=\odot_{(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{4}} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)} \in \mathbb{R}^{2^{\left(\frac{p_{k}\left(p_{k}-1\right)}{2}-p_{k-1}\left(2 p_{k-1}-1\right)}\right) \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}}
\end{aligned}
$$

In the case $p_{k}=2 p_{k-1}$, the number of entries in the fourth block is $\frac{p_{k}\left(p_{k}-1\right)}{2}-p_{k-1}\left(2 p_{k-1}-1\right)=0$, so we replace the definition of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ by $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}=\mathbf{1}^{\top} \in \mathbb{R}^{1 \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$.

Following the definition (B.15), by appropriately reordering the rows of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}$, we have $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}=$ $\odot_{1 \leq \ell \leq 4} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[\ell]}$. Recall that $\operatorname{vec}(\cdot)$ denotes the vectorization of a tensor or matrix and $\llbracket \cdot, \cdot, \cdot \rrbracket$ is the three-way operator defined in (B.1). By appropriately reordering the rows in $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}$, we further have

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda} \mathbf{v}=\operatorname{vec}\left(\llbracket \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]},\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\rrbracket\right)
$$

which bridges the connection between Lemma B. 2 and the CP decomposition of three-way tensors. To apply Theorem B. 1 on the CP decomposition uniqueness to the three-way tensor $\llbracket \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]},\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot\right.$ $\left.\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\rrbracket$, we need the Kruskal's condition

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)+\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}\right)+\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right) \geq 2\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|+2
$$

We now study the invertibility of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}$ and the pairwise linear independence of the columns in $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]}$, which together could ensure (B.17), as shown in the following.

We first show that $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ is invertible, so that its Kruskal rank is $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$. We denote $\lambda^{\star}:=$ $e^{C_{k}} /\left(1+e^{C_{k}}\right)$ and define for each $(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{1}$ the matrix

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}^{\prime}:=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -\lambda^{\star} \\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{ll}
1 & 0 \\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right) \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}
$$

which is a $2 \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ matrix obtained by subtracting the first row of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}$ entrywise by $\lambda^{\star}$ and making the second row all-ones. Similar to (B.15), we define

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}:=\odot_{(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{1}} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}^{\prime}
$$

Using the formula $\left(\otimes_{i=1}^{c} \mathbf{C}_{i}\right)\left(\otimes_{i=1}^{c} \mathbf{D}_{i}\right)\left(\odot_{i=1}^{c} \mathbf{E}_{i}\right)=\odot_{i=1}^{c}\left(\mathbf{C}_{i} \mathbf{D}_{i} \mathbf{E}_{i}\right)$ for matrices $\mathbf{C}_{i}, \mathbf{D}_{i}, \mathbf{E}_{i}$ of compatible dimensions, we obtain

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -\lambda^{\star} \\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)^{\otimes \frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}}\left(\begin{array}{ll}
1 & 0 \\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right)^{\otimes \frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}
$$

where $\mathbf{D}^{\otimes c}$ of a matrix $\mathbf{D}$ denotes the Kronecker product $\otimes_{i \in[c]} \mathbf{D}$. On the right hand side of (B.18), we note that the first term is a upper-triangular square matrix with diagonal all ones and the second term is a lower-triangular square matrix with diagonal all ones, which are both invertible. Therefore, $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ is invertible if and only if $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}$ is invertible.

We define the lexicographical order between any two distinct adjacency matrices $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}$ as $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succ_{l e x} \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}$ if and only if there exists $(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ such that

$$
X_{k-1, s, t}>\widetilde{X}_{k-1, s, t}, \quad X_{k-1, i, j}=\widetilde{X}_{k-1, i, j} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle: i<s \text { or }(i=s, j<t)\right\}
$$

If we vectorize the upper triangular off-diagonal entries $(i, j)$ of $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}$ in ascending order of $p_{k-1} i+j$ and view the resulting binary vector as a binary number, then the lexicographical order is exactly the order of this binary number. Recall that we have previously let $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ be an arbitrary bijective map from $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$. Within this proof, we can specify it as the unique bijective map that is monotonically decreasing, such that

$$
\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)<\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}\right) \Longleftrightarrow \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succ_{l e x} \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}, \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}
$$

Note that any other choice of bijective map $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ will only complicate our proof statement but not affect our result. We also define a permutation matrix $\mathbf{N} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{p-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{p-1}\right|}$ such that

$$
\left(\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)_{s}=\odot_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{i, j}\right)_{2-\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}}
$$

for $(\mathbf{B})_{s}$ denoting the $s$ th row of matrix $\mathbf{B}$. Then the $(s, t)$ th entry of $\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}$ is given by

$$
\left(\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}\right)_{s, t}=\prod_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(\left(\lambda_{(i, j), 1, t}-\lambda^{\star}\right) 1_{\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}=1}+1_{\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}=0}\right)
$$

where $\lambda_{(i, j), 1, t}$ denotes the $(1, t)$ th entry of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}$.
Since $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ takes the blockwise form (B.13) with $\mathbf{P}_{k}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k}}$, we have each $\Gamma_{k, i, j}>0$ and $\mathbf{a}_{k, i}=\mathbf{e}_{i}$ for $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, which implies

$$
\lambda_{(i, j), 1, t}=\frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\Gamma_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)}=\frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{i, j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{i, j}\right)}>\lambda^{\star}
$$

whenever $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{i, j}=1$. From (B.20), all the diagonal entries of $\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}$ are therefore positive. For $1 \leq s<t \leq\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$, since $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s) \succ_{l e x} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)$, there exists $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ such that $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}=1$ and $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{i, j}=0$, which implies

$$
\left(\lambda_{(i, j), 1, t}-\lambda^{\star}\right) 1_{\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}=1}+1_{\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}=0}=\frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{i, j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{i, j}\right)}-\lambda^{\star}=0
$$

From (B.20), all the upper-triangular off-diagonal entries $\left(\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}\right)_{s, t}$ are therefore zero. As a result, the $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ matrix $\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}$ is lower-triangular with positive diagonal entries. This proves that $\mathbf{N} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}^{\prime}$ is invertible, as is $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$, and $\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)=\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$. With the same procedure, we can also prove that $\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}\right)=\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$.

We next show that $\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})$ has Kruskal rank $\geq 2$. Since each column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ sums to one and each entry of $\mathbf{v}$ is positive by $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and our model formulation (2.5), it suffices to show that $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ does not have two identical columns. We prove by contradiction. Suppose the two distinct columns $s, t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$ of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ are identical. By taking partial sums, we obtain that the $s$ th and $t$ th columns of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}$ are also identical for all $(i, j) \in \mathcal{I}_{3}$. Let $s<t$, then $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s) \succ_{l e x} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)$, so there exists $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ such that $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)_{i, j}=1$ and $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)_{(i, j)}=0$. Since $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ takes the blockwise form of (B.13) with $\mathbf{P}_{k}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k}}$, we have $\mathbf{a}_{k, i}=\mathbf{e}_{i}$ and $\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}=\mathbf{e}_{j}$, which implies

$$
\lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, s}=\frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)}=\frac{e^{C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j}}}{1+e^{C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j}}}
$$

and

$$
\lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, t}=\frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)}=\frac{e^{C_{k}}}{1+e^{C_{k}}}
$$

We need to have $\lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, s}=\lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, t}$ due to the two identical columns, which implies $\Gamma_{k, i, j}=0$, contradicting with $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}$. Therefore, we have proven

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right) \geq 2
$$

For simplicity, we denote $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]}:=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$. Now that

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)+\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}\right)+\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right) \geq 2\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|+2
$$

we can apply Theorem B. 1 and obtain that for any $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[1]}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[2]}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[34]}, \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}$ of the same dimensions as $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]}, \mathbf{v}$ satisfying

$$
\left\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[1]}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[2]}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\widetilde{\mathbf{v}})\right\|=\left\|\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right\|
$$

there must exist diagonal matrices $\mathbf{Q}_{1}, \mathbf{Q}_{2}, \mathbf{Q}_{34} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ satisfying $\mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{Q}_{2} \mathbf{Q}_{34}=\mathbf{I}_{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ and permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ such that

$$
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[1]}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]} \mathbf{Q}_{1} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[2]}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]} \mathbf{Q}_{2} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\widetilde{\mathbf{v}})=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v}) \mathbf{Q}_{34} \mathbf{P}
$$

Since each column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[i]}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[i]}(i \in\{1,2,34\})$ needs to sum to one, we must have $\mathbf{Q}_{1}=\mathbf{Q}_{2}=\mathbf{Q}_{34}=$ I. Therefore, we have

$$
\begin{gathered}
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[1]}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[2]}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]} \mathbf{P} \\
\widetilde{\mathbf{v}}=\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\widetilde{\mathbf{v}})\right)^{\top} \mathbf{1}=\mathbf{P}^{\top} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v}) \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=\mathbf{P}^{\top} \mathbf{v}
\end{gathered}
$$

and

$$
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[34]}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v}) \mathbf{P} \operatorname{diag}(\widetilde{\mathbf{v}})^{-1}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v}) \mathbf{P}\left(\mathbf{P}^{\top} \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})^{-1} \mathbf{P}\right)=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[34]} \mathbf{P}
$$

Together they imply

$$
\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}:=\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[1]} \odot \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[2]} \odot \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{[34]}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}=\mathbf{P}^{\top} \mathbf{v}
$$

Proof of Lemma B.3. We define $\mathcal{P}:=\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, then $\mathcal{P}$ is a permutation map on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. Lemma B. 3 can be restated using $\mathcal{P}$ as follows: If for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$,

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

then there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ such that $\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)=\mathbf{P} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}^{\top}$ for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$.

To prove Lemma B.3, we first discuss some properties of $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ that hold for arbitrary $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$. Notice that knowing $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ is equivalent to knowing

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

which is further equivalent to knowing

$$
\operatorname{logit} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}=1 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

due to our model formulation (2.5) and (2.6). We let $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ denote the $2^{\frac{p_{k}\left(p_{k}-1\right)}{2}}$ dimensional vector

$$
\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left(\text { logit } \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}=1 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right)_{\left(i, j\right) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle}
$$

with an arbitrarily fixed order of $(i, j)$ pairs in $\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$. For two vectors $\mathbf{g}, \widetilde{\mathbf{g}} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ of the same dimension $d$, we define the partial order $\succeq$ by

$$
\mathbf{g} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{g}} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad g_{i} \geq \widetilde{g}_{i} \quad \forall i \in[d]
$$

where $g_{i}, \widetilde{g}_{i}$ denote the $i$ th entries of $\mathbf{g}, \widetilde{\mathbf{g}}$. Similarly, we also define a partial order $\succeq$ on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ by

$$
\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad X_{k-1, i, j} \geq \widetilde{X}_{k-1, i, j} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

for any $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. We let $\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ denote the collection of all $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ with $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, i.e. the set of vectors

$$
\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right\}
$$

Let $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ be an arbitrary parameter and $k \in[K]$. Since each entry $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ is positive, the set $\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ obtains a unique minimal element $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ under the partial order $\succeq$. We denote the set after removing this minimal element by

$$
\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \cap\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right\}^{c}
$$

Since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{1}$, for each $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ there exists row $r_{i} \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ such that $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}}=\mathbf{e}_{i}$. Therefore, for any $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, we have the equivalence

$$
\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \succeq \mathbf{g}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}
$$

For $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$, let $\mathbf{E}_{i, j}:=\mathbf{e}_{i} \mathbf{e}_{j}^{\top}+\mathbf{e}_{j} \mathbf{e}_{i}^{\top} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$. We notice that under the partial order $\succeq$, the set $\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ admits $\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}$ minimal elements, forming the subset

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

For $(r, s) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, let $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)_{(r, s)}$ denote the $(r, s)$ th entry of the vector $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ defined in (B.22). For each row $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$, we further define a subset of $\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ as

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left\{\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \exists s \in\left[p_{k}\right] \cap\{r\}^{r} \text { s.t. } \mathbf{g}_{(r, s)}>\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)_{(r, s)}\right\}
$$

which essentially contains all vectors $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ 's with $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ satisfying $A_{k, r, i}=$ 1 or $A_{k, r, j}=1$. For any $(r, s) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, we notice that the following equivalence holds:

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \supset \mathcal{G}_{m, s}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \succeq \mathbf{a}_{k, s} \quad \text { or } \quad \mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \geq p_{k-1}-1
$$

We consider the case $p_{k-1} \geq 3$ for now. The collection of all rows in $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ after removing the zero vector is the set $\left\{\mathbf{a}_{k, r}: r \in\left[p_{k}\right]\right\} \cap\{\mathbf{0}\}^{c}$, and since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{1}$, it contains $p_{k-1}$ minimal elements $\mathbf{e}_{1}, \ldots, \mathbf{e}_{p_{k-1}}$ under the partial order $\succeq$. Correspondingly, (B.25) suggests that the collection of sets $\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): r \in\left[p_{k}\right]\right\} \cap\{\varnothing\}^{c}$ also contains $p_{k-1}$ minimal elements under the partial order of set inclusion, which we denote by $\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(1)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right), \ldots, \mathcal{G}_{m}^{\left(p_{k-1}\right)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$. For each $\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$, there exists some row $r_{\ell} \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ and some $i_{\ell} \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ satisfying $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{\ell}}=\mathbf{e}_{i_{\ell}}$, such that

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}_{m, r_{\ell}}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i_{\ell}, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right] \cap\left\{i_{\ell}\right\}^{c}\right\}
$$

which contains exactly $p_{k-1}-1$ elements. Additionally, we also note that each $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ belongs to exactly two of the sets $\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ 's. Therefore, there exists a permutation map $\mathcal{Q}$ on $\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ satisfying

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\mathbb{Q}(i))}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \cap \mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\mathbb{Q}(j))}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right\}
$$

for all $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$.
We note that all above definitions of $\mathbf{g}, \mathcal{G}, \mathcal{G}_{0}, \mathcal{G}_{m}, \mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}$ are made based on the distributions $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ 's for $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, without explicitly knowing $\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$. Therefore, for any $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$, if (B.21) holds for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, then we have

$$
\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

and if $p_{k-1} \geq 3$, we further have

$$
\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}=\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}
$$

When $p_{k-1} \geq 3$, from (B.26) we know there further exists a permutation map $\widetilde{\Omega}$ on $\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ such that

$$
\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{\widetilde{\Omega}(i), \widetilde{\Omega}(j)}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

The above results together suggest

$$
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right)=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \quad \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right)=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{\widetilde{\Omega}(i), \widetilde{\Omega}(j)} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

Combining with (B.21) and (B.23), for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, we know the following equivalence holds for $\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \succeq \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{\widetilde{\Omega}(i), \widetilde{\Omega}(j)} & \Longleftrightarrow \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \succeq \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right) \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \mathbf{g}\left(\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right) \succeq \mathbf{g}\left(\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right) \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \succeq \mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succeq \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}
\end{aligned}
$$

This suggests that the permutation map $\mathcal{P}$ on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ is uniquely determined through the permutation map $\widetilde{\Omega}$ on $\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, and the entries of $\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)$ satisfy the equivalence

$$
\left(\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)\right)_{\widetilde{\Omega}(i), \widetilde{\Omega}(j)}=1 \quad \Longleftrightarrow X_{k-1, i, j}=1, \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

When $p_{k-1}=2$, the set $\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ contains the single element $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ and the set $\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)$ contains the single element $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)$, so we must have

$$
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right)=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \quad \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}\right)=\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}
$$

suggesting that (B.27) holds with the permutation map $\widetilde{\Omega}$ being the identity map on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}=$ $\left\{\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}\right\}$.

In either case of $p_{k-1}$, letting $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ denote the permutation matrix associated with the permutation map $\widetilde{\Omega}$ in (B.27), i.e.

$$
\left(12 \cdots p_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{P}=\left(\widetilde{\Omega}(1) \widetilde{\Omega}(2) \cdots \widetilde{\Omega}\left(p_{k-1}\right)\right)
$$

then we have

$$
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)=\mathbf{P} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}^{\top}, \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}
$$

Proof of Lemma B.4. We notice that

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}\left|\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right.
$$

is equivalent to

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1},(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

which is further equivalent to

$$
C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}=\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}, \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1},(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

We let $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}$ and take minimums

$$
\min _{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle}\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right), \quad \min _{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle}\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right)
$$

Since $\mathbf{A}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}} \in \mathcal{A}_{1}$, the minimums are respectively $C_{k}, \widetilde{C}_{k}$ and needs to equal by (B.28). Hence we obtain $\widetilde{C}_{k}=C_{k}$.

We define a partial order $\succeq$ on $\{0,1\}^{p_{k-1}}$ as

$$
\mathbf{a}_{k, r} \succeq \mathbf{a}_{k, s} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad A_{k, r, j} \geq A_{k, s, j} \quad \forall j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]
$$

We notice for any $(r, s) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, since $\mathbf{A}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}} \in \mathcal{A}_{1}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Theta}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}$, using (B.28) we have the equivalence

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, s} \\
\Longleftrightarrow & \widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, t} \geq \widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, s}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, t} \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}, t \in\left[p_{k}\right] \cap\{r, s\}^{c} \\
\Longleftrightarrow & C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, r}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, t} \geq C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, s}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, t} \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}, t \in\left[p_{k}\right] \cap\{r, s\}^{c} \\
\Longleftrightarrow & \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \succeq \mathbf{a}_{k, s}
\end{aligned}
$$

This suggests that $\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}=\mathbf{0}$ if and only if $\mathbf{a}_{k, r}=\mathbf{0}$. For the collections of non-zero rows in $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}$ given by

$$
\mathcal{R}_{k}:=\left\{\mathbf{a}_{k, r}: r \in\left[p_{k}\right], \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \neq \mathbf{0}\right\}, \quad \widetilde{\mathcal{R}}_{k}:=\left\{\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}: r \in\left[p_{k}\right], \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r} \neq \mathbf{0}\right\}
$$

each collection has the same $p_{k-1}$ minimal elements $\mathbf{e}_{1}, \ldots, \mathbf{e}_{p_{k-1}}$. From (B.29) we know any nonzero $\mathbf{a}_{k, r}$ is a minimal element of $\mathcal{R}_{k}$ if and only if $\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}$ is a minimal element of $\widetilde{\mathcal{R}}_{k}$. This implies that for all $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$, we have $\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}=\mathbf{e}_{i}$ for some $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ if and only if $\mathbf{a}_{k, r}=\mathbf{e}_{j}$ for some $j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$. We let $\mathcal{E}$ denote the collection of row index $r$ 's satisfying $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{a}_{k, r}=\mathbf{1}^{\top} \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}=1$, then for $r \in \mathcal{E}$ and $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ we have the equivalence

$$
\begin{aligned}
\widetilde{A}_{k, r, i}=1 & \Longleftrightarrow \forall s \in \mathcal{E} \cap\{r\}^{c}, \exists j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right] \cap\{i\}^{c} \text { s.t. } \widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right)\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, s}>\widetilde{C}_{k} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \forall s \in \mathcal{E} \cap\{r\}^{c}, \exists j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right] \cap\{i\}^{c} \text { s.t. } C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, r}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, s}>C_{k} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow A_{k, r, i}=1
\end{aligned}
$$

This further suggests that for all $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ and any $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right], \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r}=\mathbf{e}_{i}$ if and only if $\mathbf{a}_{k, r}=\mathbf{e}_{i}$. Since $\mathbf{A}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}} \in \mathcal{A}_{1}$, we can find $2 p_{k-1}$ distinct rows $r_{1}, \ldots, r_{p_{k-1}}, r_{1}^{\prime}, \ldots, r_{p_{k-1}}^{\prime}$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}$ satisfying

$$
\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{j}}=\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{j}}=\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{j}^{\prime}}=\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{j}^{\prime}}=\mathbf{e}_{j}, \quad \forall j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]
$$

Then for all $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ and $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, we have the equivalence

$$
\begin{aligned}
\widetilde{A}_{k, r, i}=1 & \Longleftrightarrow \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{i}} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \succeq \mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow A_{k, r, i}=1
\end{aligned}
$$

This shows that $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}=\mathbf{A}_{k}$. We notice that (B.29) has implicitly assumed $p_{k} \geq 3$. In the corner case of $p_{k}=2$, we automatically have $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}=(11)^{\top}=\mathbf{A}_{k}$ due to the definition of $\mathcal{A}_{1}$.

By letting $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}$ and using (B.28), we have for all $i \in\left[p_{k}\right]$

$$
\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, i, i}=\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{i}}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}} *\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}\right)\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{i}^{\prime}}=C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma} *\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}\right)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}^{\prime}}=C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, i}
$$

which suggests $\operatorname{diag}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{diag}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}\right)$. We also have for all $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$

$$
\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, i, j}=\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{i}}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}} *\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}\right)\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, r_{j}}=C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma} *\left(\mathbf{1 1}^{\top}\right)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, r_{j}}=C_{k}+\Gamma_{k, i, j}
$$

which suggests off-diag $\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k}\right)=$ off-diag $\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}\right)$. Together they imply $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$.

# B. 4 Holomorphic Function and Its Zero Set 

Theory of generic identifiability has been established for latent class models (Allman et al., 2009) and constrained latent class models (Gu and Dunson, 2023), where the notion of algebraic variety from algebraic geometry is used. An algebraic variety refers to the set of simultaneous zeros of a finite number of polynomial functions (Cox et al., 2013). In both models, generic identifiability is defined in terms of continuous parameters and established in two steps: We first show that the set of non-identifiable parameters lies in an affine algebraic variety, then find the existence of an identifiable parameter within the parameter space. Using the fact that the Lebesgue measure of an algebraic variety is positive if and only if all the polynomial functions defining the algebraic variety are constant zero functions, we obtain that the parameters are generically identifiable.

Our model contains both discrete $\mathbf{A}$ and continuous $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ parameters, so we have extended the definition of generic identifiability as in Definition 3.2. We aim at showing for any fixed parameter $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, the set of $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ making parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ non-identifiable has Lebesgue measure zero in $\mathcal{T}_{0}$. These sets of $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$, however, are hard to include in algebraic varieties. To handle them properly, we use the notion of a holomorphic function and the identity theorem from complex analysis (Stein and Shakarchi, 2010), which studies the zeros of holomorphic functions.

A function of several complex variables is said to be holomorphic if it is complex-differentiable within its domain, or equivalently, if it satisfies Cauchy-Riemann equations in each variable within its domain. The following theorem, widely known as the identity theorem, states that a holomorphic function of one complex variable is identically zero if its zero set contains a limit point.

Theorem B. 5 (Identity Theorem). Let $f(z)$ be a holomorphic function in a connected region $\Omega \subset \mathbb{C}$. If the zero set of $f$ has a limit point in $\Omega$, then $f \equiv 0$ in $\Omega$.

For proof of Theorem B.5, see Stein and Shakarchi (2010). Using Theorem B.5, we can obtain a theorem on the Lebesgue measure of the zero set, which can be applied to the theory of generic identifiability. While Theorem B. 5 only holds for holomorphic functions of one complex variable (e.g. $f\left(z_{1}, z_{2}\right)=z_{1} z_{2}$ is a counterexample with two complex variables), our theorem can be established for holomorphic functions of several complex variables.

Theorem B.6. Let $\Omega_{1}, \ldots, \Omega_{n} \subset \mathbb{C}$ be connected regions and $f\left(z_{1}, \ldots, z_{n}\right)$ be a holomorphic function in the region $\Omega=\Omega_{1} \times \cdots \times \Omega_{n} \subset \mathbb{C}^{n}$. If its zero set in $\mathbb{R}^{n} \cap \Omega$ has Lebesgue measure

$$
\lambda\left(\left\{x \in \mathbb{R}^{n} \cap \Omega: f(x)=0\right\}\right)>0
$$

then $f \equiv 0$ in $\Omega$.
Importantly, Theorem B. 6 suggests a general technique for showing generic identifiability, which involves two steps: We first show that the set of non-identifiable parameters are contained within the zero set of a holomorphic function. We then prove the existence of an identifiable parameter within the parameter space. Together they would imply that the set of non-identifiable parameters are contained within the zero set of a non-constant holomorphic function, which by Theorem B. 6 has Lebesgue measure zero.

Since holomorphic functions not only include polynomial functions, but also rational functions, exponential functions, trigonometric functions, as well as their compositions, this method is a generalization of the algebraic variety method described earlier. Specifically, the simultaneous zero set of polynomials $f_{1}, \ldots, f_{n}$ in $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ can be written as $\left\{x \in \mathbb{R}^{n}:\left(f_{1}^{2}+\ldots+f_{n}^{2}\right)(x)=0\right\}$, where $f_{1}^{2}+\ldots+f_{n}^{2}$ is a holomorphic function over $\mathbb{C}^{n}$.

We note that many results exist on the zero set of holomorphic functions and Theorem B. 6 should not be anything new. However, these results typically come from complex analysis and do not appear in the form of our theorem. For completeness, we present an elementary proof as below. We also note that other results from complex analysis, e.g. the Hadamard factorization theorem, also have applications in statistical theory (Gassiat et al., 2020, 2022).

Proof of Theorem B.6. We prove by induction. For $n=1$, let $f$ be a holomorphic function in $\Omega \subset \mathbb{C}$ that is not constantly zero. Using Theorem B. 5 we know the zero set of $f$ in $\mathbb{R} \cap \Omega$, denoted by $E:=\{x \in \mathbb{R} \cap \Omega: f(x)=0\}$, does not have a limit point in $\mathbb{R} \cap \Omega$. Therefore, for any $x \in E$, there exists $r_{x}>0$ such that $E \cap\left(x-r_{x}, x+r_{x}\right)=\{x\}$. This implies that the intervals $\left\{\left(x-\frac{r_{x}}{2}, x+\frac{r_{x}}{2}\right): x \in E\right\}$ are disjoint. Since each interval contains a distinct rational number, we know $E$ is countable. Let $\left\{e_{n}\right\}_{n=1}^{N}$ be an enumeration of $E$ with $N \in \mathbb{N} \cup\{\infty\}$. For

any $\epsilon>0$, we notice that the open intervals $\left\{\left(e_{n}-\frac{\epsilon}{2^{n+1}}, e_{n}+\frac{\epsilon}{2^{n+1}}\right)\right\}_{n=1}^{N}$ cover $E$, which implies $\lambda(E) \leq \sum_{n=1}^{N} \frac{\epsilon}{2^{n}} \leq \epsilon$. Therefore, the Lebesgue measure of $E$ is $\lambda(E)=0$, suggesting that Theorem B. 6 holds for $n=1$.

We now suppose that Theorem B. 6 holds for $n-1$ and consider a holomorphic function $f$ of $n$ complex variables in $\Omega \subset \mathbb{C}^{n}$ satisfying

$$
\lambda\left(\left\{x \in \mathbb{R}^{n} \cap \Omega: f(x)=0\right\}\right)>0
$$

For notational simplicity, we denote $x_{-n}:=\left(x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n-1}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{n-1}, z_{-n}:=\left(z_{1}, \ldots, z_{n-1}\right) \in \mathbb{C}^{n-1}$, and $\Omega_{-n}:=\Omega_{1} \times \cdots \Omega_{n-1} \subset \mathbb{C}^{n-1}$. We define the set

$$
B:=\left\{x_{-n} \in \mathbb{R}^{n-1} \cap \Omega_{-n}: \lambda\left(\left\{x_{n} \in \mathbb{R} \cap \Omega_{n}: f\left(x_{-n}, x_{n}\right)=0\right\}\right)>0\right\}
$$

which contains all $x_{-n} \in \mathbb{R}^{n-1} \cap \Omega_{-n}$ such that the function $g\left(x_{n}\right):=f\left(x_{-n}, x_{n}\right)$ has zero set of positive Lebesgue measure in the region $\mathbb{R} \cap \Omega_{n}$. By Fubini's theorem,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda\left(\left\{x \in \mathbb{R}^{n} \cap \Omega: f(x)=0\right\}\right) & =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n} \cap \Omega} 1_{f(x)=0} \mathrm{~d} x \\
& =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n-1} \cap \Omega_{-n}} \int_{\mathbb{R} \cap \Omega_{n}} 1_{f\left(x_{-n}, x_{n}\right)=0} \mathrm{~d} x_{n} \mathrm{~d} x_{-n} \\
& =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n-1} \cap \Omega_{-n}} \lambda\left(\left\{x_{n} \in \mathbb{R} \cap \Omega_{n}: f\left(x_{-n}, x_{n}\right)=0\right\}\right) \mathrm{d} x_{-n} \\
& =\int_{B} \lambda\left(\left\{x_{n} \in \mathbb{R} \cap \Omega_{n}: f\left(x_{-n}, x_{n}\right)=0\right\}\right) \mathrm{d} x_{-n}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, (B.30) implies that $B$ must have positive Lebesgue measure in $\mathbb{R}^{n-1}$.
For each $x_{-n} \in B$, the function $g\left(z_{n}\right):=f\left(x_{-n}, z_{n}\right)$ is a holomorphic function of $z_{n}$ in region $\Omega_{n}$. By (B.31), we have

$$
\lambda\left(\left\{x_{n} \in \mathbb{R} \cap \Omega_{n}: g\left(x_{n}\right)=0\right\}\right)>0
$$

Applying Theorem B. 6 to $g$ in region $\Omega_{n}$ implies that $g\left(z_{n}\right) \equiv 0$ in $\Omega_{n}$, that is,

$$
f\left(x_{-n}, z_{n}\right)=0, \quad \forall x_{-n} \in B, z_{n} \in \Omega_{n}
$$

Now for each $z_{n} \in \Omega_{n}$, the function $h\left(z_{-n}\right):=f\left(z_{-n}, z_{n}\right)$ is a holomorphic function of $z_{-n}$ in region $\Omega_{-n}$. Since

$$
\lambda\left(\left\{x_{-n} \in \mathbb{R}^{n-1} \cap \Omega_{-n}: h\left(x_{-n}\right)=0\right\}\right) \geq \lambda(B)>0
$$

applying Theorem B. 6 to $h$ in region $\Omega_{-n}$, we obtain $h\left(z_{-n}\right) \equiv 0$ on $\Omega_{-n}$, that is,

$$
f(z)=0, \quad \forall z \in \Omega
$$

Hence Theorem B. 6 holds for $n$ complex variables as well.

# B. 5 An Application of Geometric Measure Theory 

Following Section B. 4 on the Lebesgue measure of the zero sets of holomorphic functions, we further develop some theory along this direction using tools from geometric measure theory (Federer, 2014; Nicolaescu, 2011), which will be useful in the later proof of generic identifiability.

To present the results, we need suitable measures on fibers of smooth maps between spaces of arbitrary dimensions. We hereby recall the definition of the Hausdorff measure. Let $(X, \rho)$ be a separable metric space and $d \geq 0$ be a fixed dimension. For any $\delta>0$ and set $E \subset X$, we define

$$
\mathrm{H}_{\delta}^{d}(U):=\frac{\pi^{\frac{d}{2}}}{2^{d} \Gamma\left(\frac{d}{2}+1\right)} \inf \left\{\sum_{j \geq 1}\left(\operatorname{diam} B_{j}\right)^{d}: U \subset \bigcup_{j \geq 1} B_{j}, \operatorname{diam} B_{j}<\delta\right\}
$$

where $B_{j}$ are arbitrary subsets of $X$. Since $\mathrm{H}_{\delta}^{d}(U)$ is non-increasing in $\delta$, we can define the $d$ dimensional Hausdorff measure of $U$ as

$$
\mathrm{H}^{d}(U):=\lim _{\delta \rightarrow 0} \mathrm{H}_{\delta}^{d}(U)
$$

We note that any Borel set of $X$ is measurable with respect to $\mathrm{H}^{d}$. When $X$ is a $d$-dimensional Riemannian manifold with $\rho$ induced by its metric tensor $g, \mathrm{H}^{d}$ coincides with the Lebesgue measure $\lambda$ on $(X, g)$. When $d=0, \mathrm{H}^{0}(U)$ equals the cardinality of the set $U$, or equivalently, $\mathrm{H}^{0}$ coincides with the counting measure $\mu$.

We also recall that a function on $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ is an analytic function if it has convergent Taylor series at every point in its domain. An analytic function on $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ is smooth and can be locally extended to a holomorphic function of $n$ complex variables. Following Theorem B.6, we further have the following result for analytic functions on $\mathbb{R}^{n}$.

Theorem B.7. Let $f, g: \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{m}(m \geq n)$ be analytic functions. Let $B \subset \mathbb{R}^{n}$ be a set satisfying

$$
\sup _{y \in \mathbb{R}^{m}} \mu\left(f^{-1}(y) \cap B\right)<\infty
$$

Then for any set $A \subset \mathbb{R}^{n}$ with measure $\lambda(A)=0$, we have

$$
\lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap B\right)=0
$$

Previously, Theorem B. 6 suggests that we can establish the generic identifiability of our model with parameter space $\mathcal{R}$ by showing that all parameters $r \in \mathcal{R}$ with $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(r) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)$ lie in zero sets of holomorphic functions that are not constantly zero. By appropriately choosing a set $E \subset \mathcal{R}$ of measure zero, comparing $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}}(r)$ with $\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}}(r)$ is often a lot easier than comparing $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)$ with $\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)$, as seen in Section B.6. However, it is important to note that

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}}(r)=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}}(r) \quad \forall r \in \mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}
$$

does not necessarily imply

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(r) \quad \forall \mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}
$$

For instance, the set of parameters in $R \cap E^{c}$ that have marginal distributions coinciding with the parameters in $E$ could have positive measure despite $E$ having measure zero (e.g. examples constructed with the Cantor function). Significantly, under the conditions on analyticity of functions and bounded cardinality of fibers $\left(\sup _{y \in \mathbb{R}^{m}} \mu\left(f^{-1}(y) \cap B\right)<\infty\right)$, Theorem B. 7 rules out these possibilities and suggests that

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}}(r)=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}}(r) \quad \forall r \in \mathcal{R} \cap E^{c}
$$

can imply

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(r) \quad \forall \mathcal{R} \cap E^{c} \cap \widetilde{E}^{c}
$$

for some additional set $\widetilde{E} \subset \mathcal{R}$ of measure zero. This provides a simple strategy of establishing generic identifiability by proving generic identifiability in a smaller parameter space that excludes an undesirable set of measure zero.

The proof of Theorem B. 7 utilizes Theorem B. 6 and the area formula for Lipschitz functions. Formal introductions and proofs of the area formula can be found in standard geometric measure theory references, e.g. Federer (2014); Krantz and Parks (2008); Simon (2014).

Proof of Theorem B.7. We start by considering the case when the set $B$ is bounded. We denote the Jacobians of functions $f$ and $g$ by $J_{f}$ and $J_{g}$. Since $f, g$ are analytic functions on $\mathbb{R}^{n}$, by the Jacobian definition we know $J_{f}^{2}$ and $J_{g}^{2}$ are also analytic functions on $\mathbb{R}^{n}$, which can be locally extended to holomorphic functions of $n$ complex variables. Applying Theorem B.6, we know

$$
\lambda\left(\left\{J_{f}=0\right\}\right)=\lambda\left(\left\{J_{g}=0\right\}\right)=0
$$

Along with the boundedness of $B$, this implies that for an arbitrary $\epsilon>0$, there exists $\delta>0$ and a set $E \subset B$ satisfying $\lambda(E)<\epsilon$ and

$$
J_{f}(x)>\delta, \quad J_{g}(x)>\delta, \quad \forall x \in B \cap E^{c}
$$

We denote $\widetilde{B}:=B \cap E^{c}$ for simplicity. Again using the boundedness of $B$ and the smoothness of $f, g$, we can find $D>0$ such that

$$
J_{f}(x)<D, \quad J_{g}(x)<D, \quad \forall x \in B \cap E^{c}
$$

We denote the constant

$$
C:=\sup _{y \in \mathbb{R}^{m}} \mu\left(f^{-1}(y) \cap B\right)<\infty
$$

Additionally, we notice that the functions $f$ and $g$ are Lipschitz on $B$.
Now by applying the area formula to the function $f$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap \widetilde{B}} J_{f}(x) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} x) & =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{m}} \mathrm{H}^{0}\left(\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap \widetilde{B}\right) \cap f^{-1}(y)\right) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} y) \\
& =\int_{g(A)} \mathrm{H}^{0}\left(\widetilde{B} \cap f^{-1}(y)\right) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} y) \\
& \leq C \mathrm{H}^{n}(g(A))
\end{aligned}
$$

since $\mathrm{H}^{0}\left(\widetilde{B} \cap f^{-1}(y)\right) \leq \mu\left(f^{-1}(y) \cap B\right) \leq C$. By applying the area formula to the function $g$, we have

$$
\int_{A} J_{g}(x) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} x)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{m}} \mathrm{H}^{0}\left(A \cap g^{-1}(y)\right) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} y) \geq \mathrm{H}^{n}(g(A))
$$

since $\mathrm{H}^{0}\left(A \cap g^{-1}(y)\right) \geq 1$ for all $y \in g(A)$.

Putting everything together, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
