\lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap B\right) & \leq \lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap \widetilde{B}\right)+\epsilon \\
& \leq \frac{1}{\delta} \int_{f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap \widetilde{B}} J_{f}(x) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} x)+\epsilon \\
& \leq \frac{C}{\delta} \mathrm{H}^{n}(g(A))+\epsilon \\
& \leq \frac{C}{\delta} \int_{A} J_{g}(x) \mathrm{H}^{n}(\mathrm{~d} x)+\epsilon \\
& \leq \frac{C D}{\delta} \lambda(A)+\epsilon \\
& =\epsilon
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $\epsilon>0$ can be chosen arbitrarily, this implies

$$
\lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap B\right)=0
$$

We now consider the general case where $B \subset \mathbb{R}^{n}$ is not necessarily bounded. We can choose a monotonically increasing sequence of sets $\left\{\mathcal{O}_{i}\right\}_{i=1}^{\infty} \subset \mathbb{R}^{n}$ such that each $\mathcal{O}_{i}$ is bounded and $\lim _{i \rightarrow \infty} \mathcal{O}_{i}=\mathbb{R}^{n}$. By defining $B_{i}:=B \cap \mathcal{O}_{i}$, previous arguments for bounded $B$ implies that

$$
\lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap B_{i}\right)=0, \quad \forall i \in \mathbb{N}
$$

We therefore obtain

$$
\lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap B\right)=\lim _{i \rightarrow \infty} \lambda\left(f^{-1}(g(A)) \cap B_{i}\right)=0
$$

# B. 6 Proof of Theorem 3.7 

Similar to the proof of Theorem 3.4, transforming the problem of model identifiability to the uniqueness of three-way tensor decomposition is an essential step of our proof. We recall our previously defined probability matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ 's and probability vectors $\mathbf{v}_{k}$ 's from (B.2), (B.3), (B.4), and (B.5), which characterize the conditional distributions $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ 's and the marginal distributions $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ 's.

In studying generic identifiability, excluding sets of $\mu \times \lambda$ measure zero will not affect the result, so in the following we define a few such sets. Let $\mathcal{T}_{1}$ be a subset of $\mathcal{T}_{0}$ defined as

$$
\mathcal{T}_{1}:=\left\{\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}: \exists k \in[K], \mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{Z}^{1+\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}+1\right)}{2}} \cap\{\mathbf{0}\}^{c} \text { s.t. } z_{C} C_{k}+\sum_{1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}} z_{(i, j)} \Gamma_{k, i, j}=0\right\}
$$

where $\mathbf{z}$ is a non-zero $\left(1+\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}+1\right)}{2}\right)$-dimensional vector of integers with $z_{C}$ and $z_{(i, j)}(1 \leq i \leq$ $j \leq p_{k-1}$ ) denoting its entries. Essentially, $\mathcal{T}_{1}$ includes all the parameters $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ satisfying, for some $k \in[K]$, a non-trivial linear combination with integer coefficients of $C_{k}$ and the upper-triangular entries in $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ equals zero. For each fixed layer $k$ and non-zero integer vector $\mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{Z}^{1+\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}+1\right)}{2}}$, the collection of $C_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ with

$$
z_{C} C_{k}+\sum_{1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}} z_{(i, j)} \Gamma_{k, i, j}=0
$$

is a hyperplane in $\mathcal{T}_{0}$ and has Lebesgue measure zero. Since there are only countably many pairs of layers $k$ and integer vectors $\mathbf{z}$, the Lebesgue measure of $\mathcal{T}_{1}$ is $\lambda\left(\mathcal{T}_{1}\right)=0$.

Recall the definition of $\mathcal{A}_{2}$ from (3.8). For any $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ and each layer $k \in[K]$, there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k} \times p_{k}}$ and matrices $\mathbf{M}_{k}, \mathbf{M}_{k}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{M}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{B}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times\left(p_{k}-2 p_{k-1}\right)}$ such that

$$
\mathbf{P}_{k} \mathbf{A}_{k}=\left(\mathbf{M}_{k} \mathbf{M}_{k}^{\prime} \mathbf{B}_{k}\right)^{\top}
$$

Without loss of generality, we can let $\mathbf{P}_{k}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k}}$. We also recall from Section B. 2 that $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ is an arbitrarily fixed bijective map from the collection of adjacency matrices $\mathcal{X}_{k}$ to the integers $\left\|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right\|$. For each layer $k \in[K]$, we define two $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ matrices $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}$ entrywise by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \Phi_{k, s, t}:=\exp \left(\sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right) \quad \forall s, t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right] \\
& \Phi_{k, s, t}^{\prime}:=\exp \left(\sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)\right) \quad \forall s, t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\Phi_{k, s, t}, \Phi_{k, s, t}^{\prime}$ denote the $(s, t)$ th entry of $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}$ and $\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}$ denotes the $(i, j)$ th entry of the matrix $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s) \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. We notice that by definition, $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}$ are closely connected to the matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}$ defined in (B.15). Specifically, $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}$ is obtained by multiplying the $t$ th column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ by the positive value

$$
\prod_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right)
$$

for $t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$, and $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}$ is obtained by multiplying the $t$ th column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}$ by the positive value

$$
\prod_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)\right)
$$

for $t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$. As seen earlier in the proof of Lemma B.2, to apply Kruskal's theorem we want to establish that the matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}$ are invertible. Therefore, for each fixed $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, we define the functions

$$
\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}):=\operatorname{det}\left(\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}\right), \quad \phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}):=\operatorname{det}\left(\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}\right)
$$

which are functions of all active entries $\nu_{i}\left(1 \leq i \leq\left|\mathcal{X}_{0}\right|-1\right)$ in $\boldsymbol{\nu}$, all $C_{k}$, and all active entries $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ $\left(1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}\right)$ in $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ for $k \in[K]$. By their definitions in (B.37), we notice that each $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ for $k \in[K]$ are holomorphic functions in the complex domain $\mathbb{C}^{d}$ of dimension

$$
d=\left(\left|\mathcal{X}_{0}\right|-1\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(1+\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}+1\right)}{2}\right)
$$

where $d$ is the dimension of all active parameters in $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$, or equivalently the dimension of $\mathcal{T}_{0}$ when viewed as a Riemannian manifold. By excluding the zero sets of these holomorphic functions from $\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$ for each $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, we have the following lemma.

Lemma B.8. Let parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$ and layer $k \in[K]$. For any matrix $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k} \in$ $\mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ and vector $\widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times 1}$ satisfying

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}=\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k} \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=1, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}^{\top} \mathbf{1}=\mathbf{1}
$$

if $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$, then there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}$ such that

$$
\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}=\mathbf{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{P}, \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}=\mathbf{P}^{\top} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}
$$

We notice that Lemma B. 8 is almost identical to Lemma B.2, except that the parameter space is changed from $\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ to $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$ and we have additionally imposed the condition on each of $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ being non-zero. Its proof similarly uses the Kruskal Theorem B. 1 and is provided in Section B.7.

From Lemma B.8, for some parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$, if $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ can not be uniquely recovered up to shuffles from the product $\mathbf{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$, then $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ must lie in the zero sets of the holomorphic functions $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ or $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for some $k \in[K]$. We want to further establish that these zero sets have Lebesgue measure zero using Theorem B.6. The following lemma shows that these holomorphic functions $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ are non-constant.
Lemma B.9. Let parameter $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ and layer $k \in[K]$. Then there exist $\boldsymbol{\Theta}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$ such that $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}\left(\boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \neq 0$.

The proof of Lemma B. 9 is deferred to Section B.7. In the proof, we exploit the structure of $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}$, utilize the Leibniz formula of their determinants, and explicitly construct valid choices of $\boldsymbol{\Theta}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$ using properties of prime numbers.

Using Theorem B. 6 with Lemmas B. 8 and B.9, we can establish that by excluding sets of measure zero from $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$, we can uniquely recover $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ from their product $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ up to shuffling of columns in $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ and entries in $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$. It is desirable to mimic the proof of Theorem 3.4 and use Lemmas B. 3 and B.4, so in the following we provide similar lemmas that work with the parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$.
Lemma B.10. Let parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$ and layer $k \in[K]$. For any two bijective maps $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}$ from $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$, if for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x), \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}^{-1}(x), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

then there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ such that for all $x \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$,

$$
\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1}^{-1}(x)=\mathbf{P} \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(x) \mathbf{P}^{\top}
$$

Lemma B.11. Let parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$ and layer $k \in[K]$. If for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

then

$$
\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}=\mathbf{A}_{k}, \quad \widetilde{C}_{k}=C_{k}, \quad \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k}=\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}
$$

The proofs of Lemmas B. 10 and B. 11 are closely connected to the proofs of Lemmas B. 3 and B.4. In generalization of space $\mathcal{A}_{1}$ to $\mathcal{A}_{2}$, each connection matrix $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ no longer necessarily contains rows of indicator vectors. The newly imposed condition $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$ helps us get around this obstacle in the proofs. We defer the proofs to Section B.7.

Putting Lemmas B.8, B.9, B.10, and B. 11 together, we now provide a proof of Theorem 3.7. Similar to the proof of Theorem 3.4, for each layer $k$ we take a three-step procedure to recover the parameters $\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$ and the probability vector $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ from $\mathbf{v}_{k}$. An induction argument then allows us to sequentially recover all parameters $\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$ from the marginal distribution $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{K} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)$ for $k=K, K-1, \ldots, 1$. Compared to the proof of Theorem 3.4, we need to take additional care for the zero measure sets excluded from the parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ using Theorems B. 6 and B.7.

Proof of Theorem 3.7. By excluding some sets of measure zero from $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$, we define a smaller parameter space

$$
\mathcal{R}:=\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right): \forall k \in[K], \psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0, \phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0\right\}
$$

and denote for each $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$

$$
\mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}:=\left\{\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}: \forall k \in[K], \psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0, \phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0\right\}
$$

For the difference between $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and $\mathcal{R}$, we have

$$
(\mu \times \lambda)\left(\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{R}^{c}\right) \leq \mu\left(\mathcal{A}_{2}\right) \lambda\left(\mathcal{T}_{1}\right)+\sum_{\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}} \sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(\lambda\left(\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}^{-1}(0)\right)+\lambda\left(\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}^{-1}(0)\right)\right)
$$

By definition of $\mathcal{T}_{1}$ in (B.32), we have $\lambda\left(\mathcal{T}_{1}\right)=0$. By Lemma B. 9 and the definition of $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}, \phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ in (B.37), for any $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ and $k \in[K]$, the functions $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ are holomorphic functions in domain $\mathbb{C}^{d}$ that are not constantly zero, with $d$ being the dimension of $\mathcal{T}_{0}$. Therefore, we can apply Theorem B. 6 to each $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}$ to obtain that $\lambda\left(\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}^{-1}(0)\right)=\lambda\left(\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}^{-1}(0)\right)=0$ for all $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ and $k \in[K]$. Since $\mathcal{A}_{2}$ has finite cardinality, we therefore obtain

$$
(\mu \times \lambda)\left(\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{R}^{c}\right)=0
$$

We notice that the proof of Theorem 3.4 does not explicitly use the properties of the parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ other than Lemmas B.2, B.3, B.4. Therefore, by working with the parameter space $\mathcal{R}$ and applying Lemmas B.8, B.10, B.11, using the very same proof we can obtain

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \quad \forall(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}
$$

To extend (B.39) to the parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$, we note that the definitions of $\mathcal{T}_{1}$ in (B.32) and $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}), \phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ in (B.37) are invariant to permutation of nodes in each layer of our Bayesian network. This implies that

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subset\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{R}^{c}, \quad \forall(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{R}^{c}
$$

which suggests

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \quad \forall(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}
$$

However, it is important to note that we do not necessarily have $\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for all $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$. We instead establish in the following the weaker result that the collection of $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$ for which $\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ has measure zero, i.e.

$$
(\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}: \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\}=0
$$

We notice that for any $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, the mapping of parameter $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}$ to its corresponding probability vector $\mathbf{v}_{K}$ (i.e. the marginal probabilities of the observed adjacency matrix $\mathbf{X}_{K}$ ) is a mapping from a lower-dimensional Euclidean space to a higher-dimensional Euclidean space, which we denote by $L_{\mathbf{A}}$. By our model formulations in (2.5) and (2.6), we can easily verify that $L_{\mathbf{A}}$ is an analytic function in $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$. We notice that the nodes at layer $k$ of our Bayesian network can be permuted in at most $p_{k}!$ ways, which suggests the cardinalities

$$
\left|\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right|=\left|\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right| \leq \prod_{k=0}^{K-1}\left(p_{k}!\right)
$$

for all parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$, due to (B.39). This implies

$$
\sup _{\mathbf{u}} \mu\left(L_{\mathbf{A}}^{-1}(\mathbf{u}) \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}\right) \leq \prod_{k=0}^{K-1}\left(p_{k}!\right)<\infty
$$

for all vector $\mathbf{u}$ having the same dimension as $\mathbf{v}_{K}$. Additionally, similar to our previous derivations we have

$$
\lambda\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}^{c}\right) \leq \lambda\left(\mathcal{T}_{1}\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(\lambda\left(\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}^{-1}(0)\right)+\lambda\left(\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}^{-1}(0)\right)\right)=0
$$

Therefore, we have verified all conditions of Theorem B.7. For any $\mathbf{A}, \mathbf{A}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, by applying Theorem B. 7 to the analytic functions $L_{\mathbf{A}}, L_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}$ and the sets $\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}^{c}, \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}$, we obtain

$$
\lambda\left(L_{\mathbf{A}}^{-1}\left(L_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}^{c}\right)\right) \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}\right)=0
$$

Taking summation over all $\mathbf{A}, \mathbf{A}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
& (\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}: \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
\leq & \sum_{\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}} \sum_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}} \lambda\left\{\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}: \exists \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}^{c} \text { s.t. }\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \in \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
= & \sum_{\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}} \sum_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}} \lambda\left(L_{\mathbf{A}}^{-1}\left(L_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}^{c}\right)\right) \cap \mathcal{R}_{\mathbf{A}}\right) \\
= & 0
\end{aligned}
$$

which proves our desired (B.41).
By combining (B.38), (B.39), (B.40), and (B.41) together, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
& (\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}: \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
\leq & (\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}: \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
& +(\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}: \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
& +(\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}: \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
= & (\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}: \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
\leq & (\mu \times \lambda)\left(\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{R}^{c}\right) \\
& +(\mu \times \lambda)\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}: \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \subsetneq \operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\} \\
= & 0
\end{aligned}
$$

which proves that our model with parameter space $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ is generically identifiable.

# B. 7 Proof of Auxiliary Lemmas for Theorem 3.7 

Proof of Lemma B.8. For a general layer $k \in[K]$, since the only probability matrix and vector involved in Lemma B. 8 are $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}, \mathbf{v}_{k-1}$, for simplicity we abbreviate $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ as $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}$ and $\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$ as $\mathbf{v}$. Similarly, we also abbreviate $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_{k}$ as $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}, \widetilde{\mathbf{v}}_{k-1}$ as $\widetilde{\mathbf{v}}$, and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k,(i, j)}$ as $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}$ for any index pair $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$. From the proof of Lemma B.2, we recall the definition of index pairs $\mathcal{I}_{1}, \mathcal{I}_{2}, \mathcal{I}_{3}, \mathcal{I}_{4} \subset\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ in (B.14) and the definition of matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ in (B.15). We have established in (B.16) that, by appropriately reordering the rows in $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}$, we have

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda} \mathbf{v}=\operatorname{vec}\left(\llbracket \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}, \left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\rrbracket\right)
$$

which bridges the connection between the uniqueness of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}, \mathbf{v}$ and the uniqueness of three-way tensor CP decomposition. A sufficient condition to apply Kruskal's Theorem B. 1 has been given earlier in (B.17), which holds if we have

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)=\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}\right)=\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|, \quad \operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right) \geq 2
$$

Let $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$ satisfy $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$. It is therefore sufficient to prove (B.42) for such an $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$.

Recalling the definition of $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ and $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ from (B.37), we know that the matrices $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Phi}_{k}^{\prime}$ are both invertible, which further implies that the matrices $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}$ are invertible due to (B.35) and (B.36). Therefore, we have

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)=\operatorname{rank}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right)=\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|, \quad \operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}\right)=\operatorname{rank}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[2]}\right)=\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|
$$

as a direct result of $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0, \phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$.
Now since $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$, we know each entry of $\mathbf{v}$ is positive. We also notice that each column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ sums to one by the definitions of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ in (B.15). Therefore, showing

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right) \geq 2
$$

is equivalent to showing that the columns of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ are distinct. We recall the lexicographic order of adjacency matrices in $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ defined in (B.19). While we have previously let $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ be an arbitrary bijective map from $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$, within this proof we specify it to be the unique monotonically decreasing map such that

$$
\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)<\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}\right) \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succ_{l e x} \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}, \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}
$$

This specification of the map $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ works solely to simplify our proof statement, while using any other choice of bijective map will not affect our result.

Suppose that the $s$ th and $t$ th columns of $\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})$ are identical, with $s<t$. Then there must exist $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ such that the entries $\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}=1$ and $\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right)_{i, j}=0$. Recall that $\langle\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y}\rangle:=\operatorname{tr}\left(\mathbf{X Y}^{\top}\right)$ is the inner product between matrices of the same size. By the definition in (B.3), the $(1, s)$ th and $(1, t)$ th entries of the probability matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right)}$ are

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, s} \\
= & \frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)} \\
= & \frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\operatorname{tr}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right)+\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s), \text { off-diag }\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right\rangle\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\operatorname{tr}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right)+\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s), \text { off-diag }\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right\rangle\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

and

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, t} \\
= & \frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j}\right)} \\
= & \frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+\operatorname{tr}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right)+\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t), \text { off-diag }\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right\rangle\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\operatorname{tr}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right)+\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t), \text { off-diag }\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right\rangle\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the $s$ th and $t$ th columns of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}$ are identical, the $s$ th and $t$ th columns of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{(i, j)}$ must also be identical. This implies $\lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, s}=\lambda_{\left(i, p_{k-1}+j\right), 1, t}$, which gives

$$
\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s), \text { off-diag }\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, t}^{\top}\right)\right\rangle=\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t), \text { off-diag }\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, p_{k-1}+j} \mathbf{a}_{k, t}^{\top}\right)\right\rangle
$$

We notice that both the left hand side and the right hand side of (B.43) are linear combinations with integer coefficients of the upper-triangular entries in $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$. Since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ has $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ taking the form of (B.33) with $\mathbf{P}_{k}$ assumed to be $\mathbf{I}_{p_{k}}$ for simplicity, we know the entries $A_{k, i, i}=A_{k, p_{k-1}+j, j}=1$. Along with $\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}=1$ and $\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right)_{i, j}=0$, this implies that the left hand side of (B.43) involves a term of $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ with positive integer coefficient whereas the right hand side of (B.43) does not. Therefore, (B.43) suggests that a non-trivial linear combination with integer coefficients of the upper-triangular entries in $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ is zero, which contradicts with $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$. Therefore, the columns of $\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})$ must be distinct, implying

$$
\operatorname{rank}_{K}\left(\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right) \geq 2
$$

We have now established the conditions in (B.42), under which Kruskal's Theorem B. 1 can be applied to the three-way tensor CP decomposition $\left\|\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]},\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[3]} \odot \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[4]}\right) \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{v})\right\|$. The remaining proof is the same as in the proof of Lemma B. 2 and hence omitted here.

Proof of Lemma B.9. We fix an arbitrary $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ and layer $k \in[K]$. Since each $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ takes the form of (B.33) with $\mathbf{P}_{k}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k}}$, the proof for existence of $\boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}$ satisfying $\phi_{\mathbf{A}, k}\left(\boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \neq 0$ is similar to the proof for existence of $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ satisfying $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$. We therefore only prove for $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ in the following.

We recall the definition of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ from (B.15) and $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ as a bijective map from $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$. Within this proof, we denote the $p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}$ upper-left principal submatrix of $\mathbf{X}_{k}$ by $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. By appropriately reordering the rows of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$, we can have the $(s, t)$ th entry of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}$ given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda_{[1], s, t}= & \mathbb{P}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k}=\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s) \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t), \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \\
= & \prod_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle} \frac{\exp \left(\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)} \\
= & \exp \left(\sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle}\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}\left(C_{k}+\left\langle\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \mathbf{a}_{k, j}^{\top}\right), \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}\right\rangle\right)\right) \\
& \cdot \exp \left(\sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle} \frac{\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}}{2}\left\langle\operatorname{off}-\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \mathbf{a}_{k, j}^{\top}+\mathbf{a}_{k, j} \mathbf{a}_{k, t}^{\top}\right), \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right\rangle\right) \\
& \cdot \prod_{\left.(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right.} \frac{1}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(t)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)} \\
:= & \beta_{s}^{(1)} \cdot \delta_{s, t} \cdot \beta_{t}^{(3)}
\end{aligned}
$$

which decomposes into the product of three terms $\beta_{s}^{(1)}, \delta_{s, t}, \beta_{t}^{(3)}$, with the first term $\beta_{s}^{(1)}$ being invariant of column $t$ and the third term $\beta_{t}^{(3)}$ being invariant of row $s$. Accordingly, we define the $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ diagonal matrices

$$
\mathbf{B}_{1}:=\operatorname{diag}\left(\beta_{1}^{(1)}, \ldots, \beta_{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}^{(1)}\right), \quad \mathbf{B}_{3}:=\operatorname{diag}\left(\beta_{1}^{(3)}, \ldots, \beta_{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}^{(3)}\right)
$$

and let $\boldsymbol{\Delta}$ be the $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ matrix with its $(s, t)$ th entry being $\delta_{s, t}$, then

$$
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}=\mathbf{B}_{1} \boldsymbol{\Delta} \mathbf{B}_{3}
$$

Since all values of $\beta_{s}^{(1)}$ and $\beta_{t}^{(3)}$ are positive, both matrices $\mathbf{B}_{1}, \mathbf{B}_{3}$ are invertible, which implies that $\psi_{\mathbf{A}}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{det}\left(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{[1]}\right) \neq 0$ is equivalent to $\operatorname{det} \boldsymbol{\Delta} \neq 0$.

Let $\iota$ denote any permutation on the integers $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$ and $\mathcal{J}$ denote the collection of all $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ ! permutations on $\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]$. The Leibniz formula for determinants gives the expansion

$$
\operatorname{det} \boldsymbol{\Delta}=\sum_{\iota \in \mathcal{J}} \operatorname{sgn}(\iota) \prod_{s=1}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|} \delta_{s, \iota(s)}=\sum_{\iota \in \mathcal{J}} \operatorname{sgn}(\iota) \exp \left(\frac{1}{2}\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}, \sum_{s=1}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}\left(\mathbf{H}_{s} *\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \iota\right)(s)\right)\right\rangle\right)
$$

where $\operatorname{sgn}(\iota)$ is the parity (oddness or evenness) of permutation $\iota$ and $\mathbf{H}_{s}$ is the $p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}$ matrix

$$
\mathbf{H}_{s}:=\text { off-diag }\left(\sum_{(i, j) \in\left(p_{k-1}\right)}\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1}(s)\right)_{i, j}\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \mathbf{a}_{k, j}^{\top}+\mathbf{a}_{k, j} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\right)\right)
$$

Recalling the definition of matrices in class $\mathcal{M}_{d}$ from Definition 3.6 and the blockwise form of connection matrix $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ from (B.33), we know

$$
\mathbf{H}_{s} \neq \mathbf{H}_{r}, \quad \forall s, r \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right], s \neq r
$$

We also recall the definition of lexicographical order between adjacency matrices from (B.19). Note that this definition extends to a complete order on any collection of symmetric matrices with zero diagonals, e.g. the collection

$$
\left\{\mathbf{H}_{s}: s \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]\right\}
$$

For any two distinct adjacency matrices $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, we have either $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \prec_{l e x} \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}$ or $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succ_{l e x} \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}$. For any two distinct integers $s \neq r$, similarly we have either $\mathbf{H}_{s} \prec_{l e x} \mathbf{H}_{r}$ or $\mathbf{H}_{s} \succ_{l e x} \mathbf{H}_{r}$. Therefore, among all the permutations in $\mathcal{J}$, there exists a unique permutation $\iota^{*}$ such that the following equivalence holds:

$$
\mathbf{H}_{s} \prec_{l e x} \mathbf{H}_{t} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \iota^{*}\right)(s) \prec_{l e x}\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \iota^{*}\right)(t), \quad \forall s, t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]
$$

For any permutation $\iota \in \mathcal{J}$, we define the $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| \times\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ matrix

$$
\mathbf{G}_{\iota}:=\sum_{s=1}^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|}\left(\mathbf{H}_{s} *\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \iota\right)(s)\right)
$$

We notice for any non-decreasing sequences of non-negative values $\left\{x_{i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n}$ and $\left\{y_{i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n}$, we have

$$
\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_{i} y_{\pi(i)} \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} x_{i} y_{i}
$$

for all permutations $\pi$ on the integers $[n]$. When the sequences $\left\{x_{i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n},\left\{y_{i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n}$ are strictly increasing, the inequality becomes equality if and only if $\pi$ is the identity permutation on $[n]$. Since all entries of $\mathbf{H}_{s}$ 's and $\left(\mathcal{X}_{k-1}^{-1} \circ \iota\right)(s)$ 's are non-negative, using this elementary inequality above, we can obtain

$$
\mathbf{G}_{\iota} \prec_{l e x} \mathbf{G}_{\iota^{*}}, \quad \forall \iota \in \mathcal{J}, \iota \neq \iota^{*}
$$

We now explicitly construct the parameter $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$ such that its corresponding $\operatorname{det} \boldsymbol{\Delta} \neq 0$. From the definition of $\delta_{s, t}$ in (B.44), we know that the parameter $C_{k}$, the diagonal entries of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$, the parameter $\boldsymbol{\nu}$, and the parameters of other layers $\boldsymbol{\Theta}_{\ell}$ for $\ell \neq k$ do not affect the invertibility of $\Delta$. Therefore, we can choose them to be any valid value such that, together with the off-diagonal entries of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ specified in the following, we can have $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$.

For the off-diagonal entries of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$, we choose them sequentially by pairs $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ in descending order of $p_{k-1} i+j$, that is, in the order

$$
\left(p_{k-1}-1, p_{k-1}\right),\left(p_{k-1}-2, p_{k-1}\right),\left(p_{k-1}-2, p_{k-1}-1\right), \ldots,(2,3),\left(1, p_{k-1}\right), \ldots,(1,2)
$$

We first construct a sequence of prime numbers

$$
q_{1}, \ldots, q_{\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}}
$$

satisfying that $q_{1} \geq 3$ and

$$
q_{t+1}>\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|!\left(\prod_{s=1}^{t} q_{s}\right)^{\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)} \quad \forall t \in\left[\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}-1\right]
$$

which always exists since there are infinitely many prime numbers. The off-diagonal entries of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ are then assigned in descending order of $p_{k-1} i+j$ to the sequence

$$
\left\{\log q_{t}\right\}_{t=1}^{\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}}
$$

We claim that the our constructed parameter $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ satisfies $\operatorname{det} \boldsymbol{\Delta} \neq 0$. To see this, we notice that the cardinality of the collection of permutations $\mathcal{J}$ is $\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|$ ! and each entry of the matrix $\mathbf{G}_{\iota}$ satisfies

$$
0 \leq G_{\iota, s, t} \leq\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right) \quad \forall s, t \in\left[\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|\right]
$$

by the definitions of $\mathbf{H}_{s}$ in (B.46) and $\mathbf{G}_{\iota}$ in (B.47). Using (B.48), for each permutation $\iota \neq \iota^{*}$ there exists an index pair $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ such that entrywise

$$
G_{\iota, s, t}=G_{\iota^{*}, s, t} \quad \forall(s, t) \in\{(s, t)<(i, j)\}, \quad G_{\iota, i, j}<G_{\iota^{*}, i, j}
$$

where for simplicity we denote the set of index pairs

$$
\{(s, t)<(i, j)\}:=\left\{(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle: s<i \text { or }(s=i, t<j)\right\}
$$

Similarly, we also denote the set of index pairs

$$
\{(s, t)>(i, j)\}:=\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle \cap\{(s, t)<(i, j)\}^{c} \cap\{(i, j)\}^{c}
$$

then our choice of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ satisfies

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \exp \left(\frac{1}{2}\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}, \mathbf{G}_{\iota^{*}}\right\rangle-\frac{1}{2}\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}, \mathbf{G}_{\iota}\right\rangle\right) \\
= & \exp \left(\Gamma_{k, i, j}\left(G_{\iota^{*}, i, j}-G_{\iota, i, j}\right)\right) \cdot \exp \left(\sum_{(s, t) \in\{(s, t)>(i, j)\}} \Gamma_{k, s, t}\left(G_{\iota^{*}, s, t}-G_{\iota, s, t}\right)\right) \\
\geq & \exp \left(\Gamma_{k, i, j}\right) \cdot \exp \left(-\sum_{\{(s, t)>(i, j)\}} \Gamma_{k, s, t}\left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right| p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)\right) \\
> & \left|\mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right|!
\end{aligned}
$$

where we have used the definitions in (B.49) and (B.50). This implies that among the terms in the expansion (B.45) of $\operatorname{det} \boldsymbol{\Delta}$, we have

$$
\exp \left(\frac{1}{2}\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}, \mathbf{G}_{i^{*}}\right\rangle\right)>\sum_{c \in \mathcal{I} \cap\left\{i^{*}\right\}^{c}} \exp \left(\frac{1}{2}\left\langle\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}, \mathbf{G}_{i}\right\rangle\right)
$$

which implies that $\operatorname{det} \boldsymbol{\Delta} \neq 0$.
As a last step of our proof, we show that $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$. Since we can choose the parameter $C_{k}$ and the diagonal entries of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ arbitrarily, it suffices to prove that any non-trivial linear combination with integer coefficients of the upper-triangular, off-diagonal entries of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ is non-zero. Suppose there exists an integer vector $\mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{Z}^{\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}}$ satisfying

$$
\sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle} z_{(i, j)} \Gamma_{k, i, j}=0
$$

In (B.50), we have associated the sequence $\left\{q_{t}\right\}_{t=1}^{\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}}$ with the sequence of index pairs in $\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ in descending order of $p_{k-1} i+j$, so we will also denote the corresponding $q_{t}$ by $q_{(i, j)}$ for simplicity. Then (B.51) implies

$$
\prod_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle} q_{(i, j)}^{z_{(i, j)}}=1
$$

Since $q_{(i, j)}$ for $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ are chosen to be distinct prime numbers in (B.49), we must have

$$
z_{(i, j)}=0, \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

Therefore, by choosing the other parameters in $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ appropriately (e.g. as logarithms of other distinct prime numbers), we have constructed a choice of $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$.

We note that our proof above works for all $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$. That is, for any $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$, through the above procedure we can construct a choice of parameter $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$ such that $\psi_{\mathbf{A}, k}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0$.

Proof of Lemma B.10. Similar to the proof of Lemma B.3, we define $\mathcal{P}:=\widetilde{\mathcal{X}}_{k-1} \circ \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, then $\mathcal{P}$ is a permutation map on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. Lemma B. 10 can be restated using $\mathcal{P}$ as follows: If for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$,

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

then there exists a permutation matrix $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ such that $\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)=\mathbf{P} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}^{\bar{\gamma}}$ for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$.

To prove Lemma B.10, we first recall some properties of $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ discussed in the proof of Lemma B.3, which extends to hold for arbitrary $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right)$. Notice that knowing $\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ is equivalent to knowing

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

which is further equivalent to knowing

$$
\operatorname{logit} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}=1 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\bar{\gamma}}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

due to our model formulation (2.5). Recall that we have defined $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ in (B.22) to be the $2^{\frac{p_{k}\left(p_{k}-1\right)}{2}}$-dimensional vector

$$
\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left(\text { logit } \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}=1 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right)_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle}
$$

with an arbitrary fixed order of $(i, j)$ pairs in $\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$. For two vectors $\mathbf{g}, \widetilde{\mathbf{g}} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ of the same dimension $d$, a partial order $\succeq$ between them is defined by

$$
\mathbf{g} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{g}} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad g_{i} \geq \widetilde{g}_{i} \quad \forall i \in[d]
$$

where $g_{i}, \widetilde{g}_{i}$ denote the $i$ th entries of $\mathbf{g}, \widetilde{\mathbf{g}}$. A partial order $\succeq$ on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ is similarly defined by

$$
\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succeq \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad X_{k-1, i, j} \geq \widetilde{X}_{k-1, i, j} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

for any $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$. We also recall that $\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ is defined to be the collection of all $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ with $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, i.e. the set of vectors

$$
\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}\right\}
$$

Let $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{\circ}\right)$ be an arbitrary parameter and $k \in[K]$. Since each entry $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ is positive, the set $\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ obtains a unique minimal element $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ under the partial order $\succeq$. We denote the set after removing this minimal element by

$$
\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \cap\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right\}^{c}
$$

If $p_{k-1}=2$, then the proof of Lemma B. 10 is the same as the proof of Lemma B.3, so we only consider the case $p_{k-1} \geq 3$ in the following. Since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \subset \mathcal{A}_{2,1}$, there exists distinct row indices

$$
r_{1}, \ldots, r_{p_{k-1}}, r_{1}^{\prime}, \ldots, r_{p_{k-1}}^{\prime} \in\left[p_{k}\right]
$$

such that $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{i}$ and $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}^{\prime}} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{i}$ for each $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$. We denote $\mathbf{E}_{i, j}:=\mathbf{e}_{i} \mathbf{e}_{j}^{\top}+\mathbf{e}_{j} \mathbf{e}_{i}^{\top} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ for $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$. Importantly, under the partial order $\succeq$, the $\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}$ elements

$$
\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right), \quad(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

are no longer necessarily the minimal elements of the set $\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$, contrary to the proof of Lemma B. 3 with $p_{k-1} \geq 3$ and $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{1}$. However, we are still able to pick out the set of these $\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}$ elements from the set $\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$, as discussed in the following.

We consider the collection $\mathcal{H}$ of all entries in the vectors

$$
\mathbf{g}-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right), \quad \mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)
$$

then each element of $\mathcal{H}$ is a linear combination with non-negative integer coefficients of the values $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ for $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$. Recall the definition of rows $r_{i}, r_{i}^{\prime}$ from (B.53). For any $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$, we have $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{i}$ and $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{j}} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{j}$. If either $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}} \nsubseteq \mathbf{e}_{j}$ or $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{j}} \nsubseteq \mathbf{e}_{i}$, then we have

$$
\left(\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right)_{r_{i}, r_{j}}=\Gamma_{k, i, j}
$$

Otherwise, we have $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{i}} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{i}+\mathbf{e}_{j}$ and $\mathbf{a}_{k, r_{j}} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{i}+\mathbf{e}_{j}$. Since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \subset \mathcal{A}_{2,2}$, the columns of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ are distinct, which implies the existence of a third row $s \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ such that either $A_{k, s, i}=1, A_{k, s, j}=0$ or $A_{k, s, i}=0, A_{k, s, j}=1$. Without loss of generality, we let the former case hold, then we have

$$
\left(\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right)_{s, r_{j}}=\Gamma_{k, i, j}
$$

By combining the two cases (B.54) and (B.55), we obtain that each upper-triangular, off-diagonal entry $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ is an element of the set $\mathcal{H}$, i.e.

$$
\mathcal{H} \supset\left\{\Gamma_{k, i, j}:(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

Since $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$, each $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ can not be expressed as a linear combination with integer coefficients of other $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ 's, which implies that $\left\{\Gamma_{k, i, j}:(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}$ is the unique subset $\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}$ of $\mathcal{H}$ of size $\frac{p_{k-1}\left\langle p_{k-1}-1\right\rangle}{2}$ satisfying

$$
\forall h \in \mathcal{H}, \exists 0 \leq m \leq \frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}, h_{1}, \ldots, h_{m} \in \mathcal{H}_{\gamma}, z_{1}, \ldots, z_{m} \in \mathbb{Z}_{+} \text {s.t. } h=\sum_{\ell=1}^{m} h_{\ell} z_{\ell}
$$

where $\mathbb{Z}_{+}$denotes the set of all positive integers. This essentially says that

$$
\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}:=\left\{\Gamma_{k, i, j}:(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

is the only subset of $\mathcal{H}$ of its size such that each element of $\mathcal{H}$ can be written as a linear combination with non-negative integer coefficients of the subset elements. Importantly, this implies that $\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}$ is well-defined given $\mathcal{H}$, without knowing the parameters $\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$ or the matrix $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ to which each $\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{0}$ corresponds. To proceed, notice that among all elements of $\mathcal{G}_{0}, \mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ is the unique element $\mathbf{g}$ satisfying that each entry of $\mathbf{g}-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ is an integer multiple of $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$. Therefore, by defining the set

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left\{\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{0}: \exists \gamma \in \mathcal{H}_{\gamma}, \mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{Z}^{\frac{p_{k-1}\left\langle p_{k-1}-1\right\rangle}{2}} \text { s.t. } \mathbf{g}-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\gamma \mathbf{z}\right\}
$$

we have

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

Based on the well-defined set $\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$, we can define its subset $\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ for each row $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ as in (B.24), given by

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):=\left\{\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{m}: \exists s \in\left[p_{k}\right] \cap\{r\}^{c} \text { s.t. }\left(\mathbf{g}-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right)_{(r, s)}>0\right\}
$$

By definition, we find that $\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ consists of all vectors $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ 's with $(i, j) \in$ $\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ satisfying $A_{k, r, i}=1$ or $A_{k, r, j}=1$, i.e.

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle,\left(A_{k, r, i}=1 \text { or } A_{k, r, j}=1\right)\right\}
$$

For any $(r, s) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, we notice that

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \supset \mathcal{G}_{m, s}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \succeq \mathbf{a}_{k, s} \quad \text { or } \quad \mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{a}_{k, r} \geq p_{k-1}-1
$$

Since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A} \subset \mathcal{A}_{2,1} \cap \mathcal{A}_{2,2} \cap \mathcal{A}_{2,3}$, we know that the columns of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ are distinct and each column contains both an entry of zero and an entry of one. We let $\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ for $\ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ denote the subset of $\mathcal{G}_{m}$ given by

$$
\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right):(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle,(i=\ell \text { or } j=\ell)\right\}
$$

then it satisfies that for all $\ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, there exists $r, s \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ such that

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \in \mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \notin \mathcal{G}_{m, s}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)
$$

and for any two distinct $\ell, \ell^{\prime} \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, there exists $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ such that either

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \in \mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{m}^{\left(\ell^{\prime}\right)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \notin \mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)
$$

or

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell^{\prime})}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \in \mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \notin \mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)
$$

Additionally, we notice for each $r \in\left[p_{k}\right]$ that

$$
\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\bigcup_{\ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]: A_{k, r, \ell}=1} \mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)
$$

Therefore, the collection of sets $\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}$ is the unique subset of size $p_{k-1}$ of the power set $2^{\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)}$ satisfying that each $\mathcal{G}_{m, r}$ can be written as a finite union of the sets in this collection. This implies that the collection $\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}$ is also well-defined given $\mathcal{G}_{m, r}$, without knowing $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ or which $\mathbf{X}_{k-1}$ each $\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{m}$ corresponds to. While $\mathcal{G}_{m, r}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ differs for different $\mathbf{A}_{k}$, by its definition, the collection $\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}$ is identical for all $\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}$ with $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$. Additionally, we also note that each $\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ belongs to exactly two of the sets $\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ 's. Therefore, there exists a permutation map $\mathcal{Q}$ on $\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ satisfying

$$
\left\{\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right\}=\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\mathcal{Q}(i))}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \cap \mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\mathcal{Q}(j))}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)
$$

for all $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$.
Now for any $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{\circ}\right)$, if (B.52) holds for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, then we have

$$
\mathcal{G}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathcal{G}_{m}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

and additionally,

$$
\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}=\left\{\mathcal{G}_{m}^{(\ell)}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right): \ell \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]\right\}
$$

From (B.59) we know there further exists a permutation map $\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}$ on $\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ such that

$$
\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(i), \widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(j)}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)
$$

which suggests

$$
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right)=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \quad \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right)=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(i), \widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(j)} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

From (B.57) and $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$, for every vector $\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$, we can decompose the entries of $\mathbf{g}-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)$ into linear combinations with non-negative integer coefficients of $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ 's and denote the collection of all $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ 's with at least one positive coefficient by $\mathcal{H}(\mathbf{g})$, i.e.

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathcal{H}(\mathbf{g}):=\left\{\Gamma_{k, i, j}:(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle, \exists(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle, \mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{Z}_{+}^{\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}} \text { s.t. } z_{(i, j)}>0\right. \\
\left.\left(\mathbf{g}-\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right)_{(s, t)}=\sum_{(u, v) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle} z_{(u, v)} \Gamma_{k, u, v}\right\}
\end{gathered}
$$

Similarly, for every vector $\mathbf{g} \in \mathcal{G}_{0}\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)$, we can decompose is entries into linear combinations with non-negative integer coefficients of $\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, i, j}$ 's and denote the collection of all $\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, i, j}$ 's with at least

one positive coefficient by $\widetilde{\mathcal{H}}(\mathbf{g})$. Then for all $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, we have the following equivalence:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \succeq \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(i), \widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(j)} & \Longleftrightarrow \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \succeq \mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right) \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \widetilde{\mathcal{H}}\left(\mathbf{g}\left(\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)\right) \succeq \widetilde{\mathcal{H}}\left(\mathbf{g}\left(\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}\right), \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right)\right) \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \mathcal{H}\left(\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right) \succeq \mathcal{H}\left(\mathbf{g}\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right) \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \succeq \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}
\end{aligned}
$$

This suggests that the permutation map $\mathcal{P}$ on $\mathcal{X}_{k-1}$ is uniquely determined through the permutation map $\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}$ on $\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, and the entries of $\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)$ satisfy the equivalence

$$
\left(\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)\right)_{\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(i), \widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(j)}=1 \quad \Longleftrightarrow X_{k-1, i, j}=1, \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

Letting $\mathbf{P} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}}$ denote the permutation matrix associated with the permutation map $\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}$, i.e.

$$
\left(\begin{array}{lllll}
1 & 2 & \cdots & p_{k-1}
\end{array}\right) \mathbf{P}=\left(\widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(1) \widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}(2) \cdots \widetilde{\mathcal{Q}}\left(p_{k-1}\right)\right)
$$

then we have

$$
\mathcal{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right)=\mathbf{P} \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mathbf{P}^{\top}, \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}
$$

Proof of Lemma B.11. Part of this proof is the same as in the proof of Lemma B.4, which we repeat in the following for completeness. We notice that

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}
$$

is equivalent to

$$
\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)=\operatorname{Law}\left(X_{k, i, j} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}, \widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}_{k}\right), \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1},(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

which is further equivalent to

$$
C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}=\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}, \quad \forall \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1},(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle
$$

We define the two sets of real values

$$
\mathcal{H}:=\left\{\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)-\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right): \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1},(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

and

$$
\widetilde{\mathcal{H}}:=\left\{\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right)-\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right): \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1},(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

then by (B.60) we have $\mathcal{H}=\widetilde{\mathcal{H}}$. As discussed earlier in (B.56) and (B.57) in the proof of Lemma B.10, since $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}$, the collection

$$
\left\{\Gamma_{k, s, t}:\left.(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}\right.
$$

is the unique subset of $\mathcal{H}$ of size $\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}$ such that every element of $\mathcal{H}$ is a linear combination with non-negative integers of the subset elements. Similarly, this relation holds for $\widetilde{\mathcal{H}}$ and its subset $\left\{\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}:\left.(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}\right.$, which implies that the two subsets

$$
\left\{\Gamma_{k, s, t}:\left.(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}=\left\{\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}:\left.(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle\right\}\right.\right.
$$

We further notice that for any $(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$,

$$
\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}\right)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)-\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)=\left(A_{k, i, s} A_{k, j, t}+A_{k, i, t} A_{k, j, s}\right) \Gamma_{k, s, t}
$$

holds for all $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$. This implies that the set

$$
\left\{\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}\right)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)-\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right):(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

is a subset of $\left\{0, \Gamma_{k, s, t}, 2 \Gamma_{k, s, t}\right\}$. Similarly, the set

$$
\left\{\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}\right)\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right)-\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right):(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

is a subset of $\left\{0, \widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}, 2 \widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}\right\}$. Along with (B.60), (B.61), and $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \notin \mathcal{T}_{1}$, we must have

$$
\Gamma_{k, s, t}=\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}, \quad \forall(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle
$$

We define a partial order $\succeq$ on $\{0,1\}^{p_{k-1}}$ as

$$
\mathbf{a}_{k, r} \succeq \mathbf{a}_{k, s} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad A_{k, r, j} \geq A_{k, s, j} \quad \forall j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]
$$

Now for each $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ and $\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}$, we let $\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{X}_{k-1}}$ denote the integer coefficients of $\Gamma_{k, s, t}$ 's with which the value

$$
\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)-\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)
$$

can be uniquely expressed as a linear combination of $\Gamma_{k, s, t}$ 's. For instance, if $\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\right.\right.$ $\left.\left.\mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)-\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)=\Gamma_{k, 2,1}+2 \Gamma_{k, 3,1}$, then $\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{X}_{k-1}}$ is the $\frac{p_{k-1}\left(p_{k-1}-1\right)}{2}$ dimensional vector with its entry corresponding to $\Gamma_{k, 2,1}$ being 1 , its entry corresponding to $\Gamma_{k, 3,1}$ being 2 , and all other entries being 0 . Similarly, we let $\widetilde{\mathbf{z}}_{(i, j), \mathbf{X}_{k-1}}$ denote the integer coefficients of $\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}$ 's of which the value

$$
\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right)-\left(\widetilde{C}_{k}+\widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, j}\right)
$$

can be uniquely expressed as a linear combination of $\widetilde{\Gamma}_{k, s, t}$ 's. From (B.60), we have

$$
\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{X}_{k-1}}=\widetilde{\mathbf{z}}_{(i, j), \mathbf{X}_{k-1}}, \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle, \mathbf{X}_{k-1} \in \mathcal{X}_{k-1}
$$

Then for each $i \in\left[p_{k}\right]$, we have the equivalence

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{a}_{k, i}=\mathbf{0} & \Longleftrightarrow \forall j \in\left[p_{k}\right], j \neq i, \mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}=\mathbf{0} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \forall j \in\left[p_{k}\right], j \neq i, \widetilde{\mathbf{z}}_{(i, j), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}=\mathbf{0} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i}=\mathbf{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

which suggests that $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}$ have the same all-zero rows.
We exclude these all-zero rows and let $\mathcal{J}$ and $\widetilde{\mathcal{J}}$ denote the collection of indices corresponding to the not all-zero rows in $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}$, then $\mathcal{J}=\widetilde{\mathcal{J}}$. For each row $i \in \mathcal{J}$ and each column $s \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, we let $y_{i, s}$ be the zero-one indicator of the event

$$
\forall t \in\left[p_{k-1}\right], t \neq s, \exists j \in \mathcal{J}, j \neq i, \text { s.t. }\left(\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}}\right)_{(s, t)}>0
$$

where $\left(\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}}\right)_{(s, t)}$ denotes the $(s, t)$ th entry of the vector $\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}}$, i.e. the integer coefficient of $\Gamma_{k, s, t}$ when writing the value

$$
\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} *\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}\right)\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)-\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)
$$

as a linear combination of the entries in $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$. Similarly, for each row $i \in \widetilde{\mathcal{J}}$ and each column $s \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, we let $\widetilde{y}_{i, s}$ be the zero-one indicator of the event

$$
\forall t \in\left[p_{k-1}\right], t \neq s, \exists j \in \widetilde{\mathcal{J}}, j \neq i, \text { s.t. }\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{z}}_{(i, j), \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{s, t}}\right)_{(s, t)}>0
$$

From (B.62) we know that

$$
y_{i, s}=\widetilde{y}_{i, s}, \quad \forall i \in \mathcal{J}=\widetilde{\mathcal{J}}, s \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]
$$

Importantly, we notice that $y_{i, s}=1$ is equivalent to saying that for any other row $j \in \mathcal{J}, j \neq i$ at least one of the two rows $\mathbf{a}_{k, i}, \mathbf{a}_{k, j}$ has its $s$ th entry equal to one. That is, we have $y_{i, s}=1$ if and only if either

$$
\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{s}
$$

or

$$
\forall j \in \mathcal{J}, j \neq i, \mathbf{a}_{k, j} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{s}
$$

For each column $s \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, we let $\mathbf{y}_{s}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{y}}_{s}$ be the $|\mathcal{J}|$-dimensional vectors with its entries being $y_{i, s}$ and $\widetilde{y}_{i, s}$ respectively, with $i \in \mathcal{J}$, then $\mathbf{y}_{s}=\widetilde{\mathbf{y}}_{s}$. We notice that if (B.63) holds for at least $|\mathcal{J}|-1$ rows in $\mathcal{J}$, then we have (B.64) holding for the remaining row in $\mathcal{J}$ (if there is one remaining), such that all entries $y_{i, s}=1$ and $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{y}_{s}=|\mathcal{J}|$. If (B.64) holds for no more than $|\mathcal{J}|-2$ rows in $\mathcal{J}$, then (B.64) can not hold for any row in $\mathcal{J}$, such that we have $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{y}_{2} \leq|\mathcal{J}|-2$. In the latter case, for each column $s \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ with $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{y}_{s} \leq|\mathcal{J}|-2$, we have for all $i \in \mathcal{J}=\widetilde{\mathcal{J}}$ that

$$
\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{s} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad y_{i, s}=1 \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \widetilde{y}_{i, s}=1 \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{s}
$$

which implies that the matrices $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}_{k}$ are identical for all columns $s$ with $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{y}_{s} \leq|\mathcal{J}|-2$. In the former case, for a column $s$ with $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{y}_{s}=|\mathcal{J}|$, restricting to the not all-zero rows in $\mathcal{J}$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$, there is at most one entry of zero in its column $s$. In such a column $s$, we notice for all $i \in \mathcal{J}=\widetilde{\mathcal{J}}$ that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{s} & \Longleftrightarrow \exists j, \ell \in \mathcal{J} \cap\{i\}^{c}, j \neq \ell, \exists t \in\left[p_{k-1}\right], t \neq s, \text { s.t. }\left(\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}\right)_{(s, t)} \neq\left(\mathbf{z}_{(i, \ell), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}\right)_{(s, t)} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \exists j, \ell \in \widetilde{\mathcal{J}} \cap\{i\}^{c}, j \neq \ell, \exists t \in\left[p_{k-1}\right], t \neq s, \text { s.t. }\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{z}}_{(i, j), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}\right)_{(s, t)} \neq\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{z}}_{(i, \ell), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}\right)_{(s, t)} \\
& \Longleftrightarrow \widetilde{\mathbf{a}}_{k, i} \succeq \mathbf{e}_{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

This is because for a column $s$ with $\mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{y}_{s}=|\mathcal{J}|$, if for some row $i \in \mathcal{J}$ we have $y_{i, s}=0$, then for any other row $j \in \mathcal{J}, j \neq i$, the integer coefficients of $\Gamma_{k, s, t}$ 's for $t \in\left[p_{k-1}\right], t \neq s$ in $\mathbf{z}_{(i, j), \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}}$ are always the same.
