$$
B^{(m)}:=\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}: \forall k \in[K], 1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}, \quad-m \leq C_{k} \leq m, \frac{1}{m} \leq \Gamma_{k, i, j} \leq m\right\}
$$

By (D.2), we can find a sequence of parameters $\left\{\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty} \subset \mathcal{A}_{1} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ such that

$$
\mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right) \in \mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)\right), \quad\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right) \notin B^{(m)}, \quad \forall m \in \mathbb{N}
$$

Since the space of probability measure $\mathcal{P}$ is compact, we can take a subsequence of $\left\{\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ such that the corresponding subsequence of probability measures $\left\{\mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ converges in $\mathcal{P}$. We can further take a subsequence, which we still denote by $\left\{\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ for notational simplicity, such that the sequence of $\mathbf{A}^{(m)}$ is constant and each sequence of $C_{k}^{(m)}$ and $\Gamma_{k, i, j}^{(m)}$ converges in the extended real line $\mathbb{R} \cup\{ \pm \infty\}$.

We recall the definitions of probability vectors and matrices $\mathbf{v}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ from (B.2), (B.3), (B.4). For each parameter $\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)$, we denote the corresponding probability vectors and matrices by $\mathbf{v}_{k}^{(m)}(k \in[0, K])$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}^{(m)}(k \in[K])$. For simplicity, we denote the collection of $\mathbf{v}_{k}^{(m)}(k \in[0, K])$ and $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}^{(m)}(k \in[K])$ by $\mathbf{W}^{(m)}$ and let $\mathcal{W}$ denote the space of all valid $\mathbf{W}$. We also denote the collection of probability vectors and matrices corresponding to the true parameter $\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)$ by $\mathbf{W}^{*}$. Since each $\mathbf{v}_{k}$ and each column of $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}$ are constrained to the probability simplex, we know $\mathcal{W}$ is homeomorphic to a product of probability simplexes and hence compact. We further notice that $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{K-1}^{(m)} \mathbf{v}_{K-1}^{(m)}$, which represents a continuous map $\mathcal{L}_{W}(\mathbf{W}):=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{K-1} \mathbf{v}_{K-1}$ from $\mathcal{W}$ to $\mathcal{P}$. For any $\mathbf{W}=\left\{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}\right\}_{k=1}^{K} \cup\left\{\mathbf{v}_{k}\right\}_{k=0}^{K} \in \mathcal{W}$, we denote the collection of all its row and column shuffled versions by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{Shuff}(\mathbf{W}):=\left\{\mathbf{W}^{\prime} \in \mathcal{W}:\right. & \exists \mathbf{P}_{k}(k \in[0, K]) \text { such that } \mathbf{v}_{K}^{\prime}=\mathbf{v}_{K} \\
& \left.\forall k \in[K], \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k}^{\prime}=\mathbf{P}_{k}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Lambda}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}, \mathbf{v}_{k-1}^{\prime}=\mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top} \mathbf{v}_{k-1}\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

where each $\mathbf{P}_{k}(k \in[0, K-1])$ is an arbitrary $p_{k} \times p_{k}$ permutation matrix and $\mathbf{P}_{K}:=\mathbf{I}_{p_{K}}$. Letting the space $\mathcal{W}$ be endowed with the $L_{1}$-distance and $\mathcal{O}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})$ denoting the $\delta$-neighborhood of $\mathbf{W}$ in $\mathcal{W}$, we consider the open set

$$
\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W}):=\bigcup_{\mathbf{W}^{\prime} \in \operatorname{Shuff}(\mathbf{W})} \mathcal{O}_{\delta}\left(\mathbf{W}^{\prime}\right)
$$

We notice that its complement $\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})^{c}$ in $\mathcal{W}$ is compact, which implies that its image $\mathcal{L}_{W}\left(\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})^{c}\right)$ under the continuous map $\mathcal{L}_{W}$ is also compact. Lemma B. 2 suggests for any $\delta>0$

$$
\mathcal{L}_{W}^{-1}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)\right)=\operatorname{Shuff}\left(\mathbf{W}^{*}\right) \subset \widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})
$$

which implies that the point $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)$ in $\mathcal{P}$ does not belong to the compact set $\mathcal{L}_{W}\left(\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})^{c}\right)$ and hence there is a positive distance between them. Therefore, for any $\delta>0$, the sequence $\left\{\mathcal{L}_{W}\left(\mathbf{W}^{(m)}\right)\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ will be eventually outside $\mathcal{L}_{W}\left(\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})^{c}\right)$, which implies that the sequence $\left\{\mathbf{W}^{(m)}\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ will be eventually within $\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\delta}(\mathbf{W})$. Since $\left\{\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ converges, we know $\left\{\mathbf{W}^{(m)}\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ converges to a point of $\operatorname{Shuff}\left(\mathbf{W}^{*}\right)$, so without loss of generality we have $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbf{W}^{(m)}=\mathbf{W}^{*}$.

Since each parameter $\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right) \notin B^{(m)}$, the convergence of the sequence $\left\{\left(\mathbf{A}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(m)}\right)\right\}$ implies that at least one of the following six statements is true for some $k \in[K]$ :
$\left(S_{1}\right) \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} C_{k}^{(m)}=-\infty$
$\left(S_{2}\right) \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} C_{k}^{(m)}=\infty$
$\left(S_{3}\right) \exists(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ s.t. $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \Gamma_{k, i, j}^{(m)}=0$
$\left(S_{4}\right) \exists(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$ s.t. $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \Gamma_{k, i, j}^{(m)}=\infty$
$\left(S_{5}\right) \exists i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ s.t. $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \Gamma_{k, i, i}^{(m)}=0$
$\left(S_{6}\right) \exists i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$ s.t. $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \Gamma_{k, i, i}^{(m)}=\infty$.
We examine each of the six statements in the following and show that contradictions with $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}=$ $\mathbf{A}_{k}^{*}$ can be found as long as one of the statements is true. Note since the sequence $\left\{\mathbf{A}^{(m)}\right\}_{m=1}^{\infty}$ is constant and in $\mathcal{A}_{1}$, by definition in (3.4) we can assume without loss of generality that each $\mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}$ takes the blockwise form of $\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}} \mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}} \mathbf{B}\right)^{\top}$.

If $S_{1}$ is true, then for any $(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ we have

$$
\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, s, t}=1 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right)=\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \frac{e^{C_{k}^{(m)}}}{1+e^{C_{k}^{(m)}}}=0
$$

If $S_{2}$ is true, then for any $(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ we have

$$
\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, s, t}=0 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right)=\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{1+e^{C_{k}^{(m)}}}=0
$$

If $S_{3}$ is true for some $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$, then for any $(s, t) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, s, t}=0 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right) \\
= & \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{1+e^{C_{k}^{(m)}}}
= & \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, s, t}=0 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where we denote $\mathbf{E}_{i, j}:=\mathbf{e}_{i} \mathbf{e}_{j}^{\top}+\mathbf{e}_{j} \mathbf{e}_{i}^{\top}$.

If $\left(\neg S_{1}\right) \wedge S_{4}$ is true for some $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$, then we have

$$
\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}=0 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}+\mathbf{E}_{i, j}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right)=\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{1+e^{C_{k}^{(m)}+\Gamma_{k, i, j}^{(m)}}}=0
$$

If $S_{5}$ is true for some $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, then we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, p_{k-1}+i, i}=0 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right) \\
= & \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{1+e^{C_{k}^{(m)}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

If $\left(\neg S_{1}\right) \wedge S_{6}$ is true for some $i \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, then we have

$$
\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, p_{k-1}+i, i}=0 \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}=\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}, \mathbf{A}_{k}^{(m)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}^{(m)}\right)=\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{1+e^{C_{k}^{(m)}+\Gamma_{k, i, i}^{(m)}}}=0
$$

Recalling the proof of Lemma B. 3 from Section B.3, we know that the probability matrix $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}^{*}$ corresponding to the parameter $\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)$ must have properties including distinct columns, nonzero entries, etc. This suggests that none of the above six equations can hold, meaning that $S_{1} \vee S_{2} \vee S_{3} \vee S_{4} \vee S_{5} \vee S_{6}$ contradicts with $\lim _{m \rightarrow \infty} \mathbf{W}^{(m)}=\mathbf{W}^{*}$. Therefore, (D.2) can not hold.

# D. 4 Quotient Parameter Space and Its Properties 

As discussed in Section D.1, to apply Proposition D. 3 and prove Doob's posterior consistency for our model, we need to get rid of the trivial non-identifiability issue coming from node permutations in each layer of our Bayesian network. We will consider the quotient of parameter space $\mathcal{R}$ defined by the equivalence relation of node permutations. We show some properties of the quotient parameter spaces in the following and prove Theorem 3.8 in the following subsection.

We consider a parameter space $\mathcal{R} \subset \mathcal{A}_{0} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ that is invariant to node permutations, i.e. satisfying $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{0} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for all $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$. Recall that $\mathcal{R}$ is endowed with the $L_{1}$-distance and the induced metric topology. Let $\mathcal{R}$ denote its Borel $\sigma$-algebra. We notice that the binary relation of $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}),\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \in \mathcal{R}$ defined by

$$
(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \sim\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})
$$

is an equivalence relation. For notational simplicity, we also use $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ to denote the equivalence class of $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ in $\mathcal{R}$. Letting $\mathcal{Q}:=\left\{\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}):(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}\right\}$ denote the collection of all the equivalence classes, we can define the map $\varphi: \mathcal{R} \rightarrow \mathcal{Q}$ as $\varphi(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}):=\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$. Since $\varphi$ is surjective, it induces the quotient topology on $\mathcal{Q}$ such that a set $U \subset \mathcal{Q}$ is open if and only if $\varphi^{-1}(U)$ is open in $\mathcal{R}$. We denote the Borel $\sigma$-algebra of the quotient topology on $\mathcal{Q}$ by $\mathcal{Q}$.

By definition of quotient topology, we know that the quotient map $\varphi$ is Borel measurable, i.e. for any $B \in \mathcal{Q}$ we have $\varphi^{-1}(B) \in \mathcal{R}$. Furthermore, the following lemma shows that the quotient map $\varphi$ also maps Borel sets in $\mathcal{R}$ to Borel sets in $\mathcal{Q}$. Note that this is a property specific for our model, which does not hold for general quotient maps.

Lemma D.6. For any Borel set $B \in \mathcal{R}$, its image $\varphi(B) \in \mathcal{Q}$.

Proof of Lemma D.6. We recall from (3.1) that every parameter in $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ corresponds to a permutation of the nodes in each layer of our model, that is, a combination of $K$ permutation matrices $\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)}:=\left\{\mathbf{P}_{0}, \ldots, \mathbf{P}_{K-1}\right\}$. Let $\mathfrak{P}$ denote the collection of all combinations $\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)}$, which has finite cardinality $|\mathfrak{P}|=\prod_{k=0}^{K-1}\left(p_{k}!\right)$. For $\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)} \in \mathfrak{P}$, we let $M_{\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)}}: \mathcal{R} \rightarrow \mathcal{R}$ be the mapping that takes a parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$ to its permuted version $\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)$ given by

$$
\forall k \in[K], \quad \mathbf{A}_{k}^{\prime}=\mathbf{P}_{k} \mathbf{A}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}, \quad C_{k}^{\prime}=C_{k}, \quad \mathbfGamma}_{k}^{\prime}=\mathbf{P}_{k-1} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{P}_{k-1}^{\top}
$$

and

$$
\forall \mathbf{X}_{0} \in \mathcal{X}_{0}, \quad \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{P}_{0} \mathbf{X}_{0} \mathbf{P}_{0}^{\top} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}^{\prime}\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right)
$$

Since $\mathcal{R}$ is invariant to node permutations, for any $\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)} \in \mathfrak{P}$ the mapping $M_{\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)}}$ is a homeomorphism on $\mathcal{R}$. We also notice that for any $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$,

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\bigcup_{\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)} \in \mathfrak{P}}\left\{M_{\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right\}
$$

Therefore, for any open set $\mathcal{O} \subset \mathcal{R}$, we have

$$
\phi^{-1}(\phi(\mathcal{O}))=\bigcup_{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{O}} \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\bigcup_{\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)} \in \mathfrak{P}} M_{\mathbf{P}_{0:(K-1)}}(\mathcal{O})
$$

which is a finite union of open sets and therefore also open. By definition of quotient topology, $\phi(\mathcal{O})$ is open in $\mathcal{Q}$. This completes the proof since the open sets generate the Borel $\sigma$-algebra.

In addition to the topological properties, we find that $\mathcal{Q}$ is also naturally a metric space. For any equivalence classes $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \in \mathcal{Q}$, we define

$$
d_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right):=\inf _{(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}^{\prime}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\prime}\right) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)}\left\|(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}})-\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}^{\prime}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{1}
$$

Having an explicit metric simplifies the verification of the quotient parameter space being a Borel subset of Polish space, which is an important condition for applying Proposition D.3.

Lemma D.7. $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is a metric on $\mathcal{R}$ that induces the quotient topology.
Proof of Lemma D.7. The positivity and symmetry of $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is direct. We notice that the mappings $M_{P_{0:(K-1)}}: \mathcal{R} \rightarrow \mathcal{R}$ defined in the proof of Lemma D. 6 are isometries under $L_{1}$-distance on $\mathcal{R}$, which suggests the simplified formula

$$
d_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right)=\inf _{(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})}\left\|(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}})-\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{1}
$$

Therefore, for any equivalence classes $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\dagger}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\dagger}\right) \in \mathcal{Q}$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& d_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right)+d_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\dagger}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\dagger}\right)\right) \\
= & \inf _{(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})}\left\|(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}})-\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{1}+\inf _{\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}^{\dagger}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\dagger}\right) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\dagger}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\dagger}\right)}\left\|\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}^{\dagger}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\dagger}\right)-\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{1} \\
\geq & \inf _{\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\right) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}^{\dagger}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\dagger}\right) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\dagger}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\dagger}\right)}\left\|\left(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}^{\dagger}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}^{\dagger}\right)-(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}})\right\|_{1} \\
= & d_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}), \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\dagger}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\dagger}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which proves the triangle inequality for $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$. Hence $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is a metric on $\mathcal{Q}$.
For any $\epsilon>0$, we let $\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ denote the $\epsilon$-neighborhood of $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ in $\mathcal{R}$ under $L_{1}$ metric and $\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right)$ denote the $\epsilon$-neighborhood of $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ in $\mathcal{Q}$ under $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ metric. We notice that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\varphi^{-1}\left(\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right)\right) & =\left\{\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right) \in \mathcal{R}: \inf _{(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})}\left\|(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}})-\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{1}<\epsilon\right\} \\
& =\bigcup_{(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}}) \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})} \mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}(\widetilde{\mathbf{A}}, \widetilde{\boldsymbol{\Theta}})
\end{aligned}
$$

which is an open set in $\mathcal{R}$. This implies that $\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right)$ is open under the quotient topology of $\mathcal{Q}$ for any $\epsilon>0$, which suggests that the metric topology induced by $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is coarser than the quotient topology.

Now for any set $\mathcal{O} \subset \mathcal{Q}$ open under the quotient topology, we know $\varphi^{-1}(\mathcal{O})$ is an open set in $\mathcal{R}$. Hence there exist an index set $\mathcal{I}$, parameters $\left\{r_{i}\right\}_{i \in \mathcal{I}} \subset \mathcal{R}$, and positive values $\left\{\epsilon_{i}\right\}_{i \in \mathcal{I}}$ such that

$$
\varphi^{-1}(\mathcal{O})=\bigcup_{i \in \mathcal{I}} \mathcal{O}_{\epsilon_{i}}\left(r_{i}\right)=\bigcup_{i \in \mathcal{I}} \bigcup_{r_{i}^{\prime} \in \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(r_{i}\right)} \mathcal{O}_{\epsilon_{i}}\left(r_{i}^{\prime}\right)=\bigcup_{i \in \mathcal{I}} \varphi^{-1}\left(\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon_{i}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(r_{i}\right)\right)\right)
$$

where the second equality is due to the definition of the quotient map $\varphi$ and the third equality is due to (D.3). This implies that $\mathcal{O}$ is the union of open balls $\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon_{i}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(r_{i}\right)\right)$ and hence open under the metric topology, which suggests that the metric topology induced by $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is finer than the quotient topology.

Putting everything together, we have shown that $\left(\mathcal{Q}, d_{\mathcal{Q}}\right)$ is a metric space and the induced metric topology is the same as the quotient topology.

# D. 5 Proof of Theorem 3.8 

After introducing the quotient parameter space and its useful properties in Section D.4, we are now ready to prove Theorem 3.8 on Doob's posterior consistency of our model using Theorem D.2, Proposition D.3, and intermediate results from the proof of Theorem 3.7 in Section B.6.

Proof of Theorem 3.8. In Section D.4, we have assumed the parameter space $\mathcal{R} \subset \mathcal{A}_{0} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ to be invariant to node permutations, i.e. $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{A}_{0} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for all $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{R}$. While this is not assumed in Theorem 3.8, we can extend the parameter space $\mathcal{R}$ to $\cup_{r \in \mathcal{R}} \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)$ and put zero prior mass on the extended regions. Note that $\cup_{r \in \mathcal{R}} \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}(r)$ is a Borel subset of $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ as long as $\mathcal{R}$ is. Therefore, without loss of generality, we will assume the parameter space $\mathcal{R}$ to be invariant to node permutations.

Recall the quotient map $\varphi$ defined in Section D.4. We let $\overline{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}$ denote the closure of $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$ and notice that it is a complete separable metric space under the $L_{1}$ distance. Using the continuity of $\varphi$ and Lemma D.7, this suggests that the quotient space $\varphi\left(\overline{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}\right)$ is a complete separable metric space under the $d_{\mathcal{Q}}$ metric and hence a Polish space.

Recall (B.38) and (B.39) from the proof of Theorem 3.7 in Section B.6. There exists a non-constant-zero holomorphic function $h_{\mathbf{A}}(\boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for each $\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}$ such that the parameter space

$$
\mathcal{D}:=\left\{(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \times\left(\mathcal{T}_{0} \cap \mathcal{T}_{1}^{c}\right): h_{\mathbf{A}}(\boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq 0\right\}
$$

satisfies the strict identifiability $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for all $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{D}$ and the measure $(\mu \times \lambda)\left(\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{D}^{c}\right)=0$. Recalling the definition of $\mathcal{T}_{1}$ from (B.32), we notice that the set

$$
\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{D}^{c}=\bigcup_{\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2}}\left(\{\mathbf{A}\} \times\left(h_{\mathbf{A}}^{-1}(0) \cup \mathcal{T}_{1}\right)\right)
$$

is Borel measurable in $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$.
Since the parameter space $\mathcal{R}$ is a Borel subset of $\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$, we know $\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}$ is also Borel measurable. Applying Lemma D. 6 further suggests that $\mathcal{Q}:=\varphi(\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D})$ is a Borel subset of the Polish space $\varphi\left(\overline{\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}}\right)$. Recall from Section D. 2 that the continuous map $\mathcal{L}: \mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D} \rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ denotes the map from parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ to the probability vector $\mathcal{L}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}):=\left\{\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{K} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)\right\}_{\mathbf{X}_{K} \in \mathcal{X}_{K}}$. Due to the trivial type of non-identifiability issue, $\mathcal{L}$ agrees on all parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ within the same equivalence class $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$, which suggests that $\mathcal{L}$ passes to the quotient, i.e. there exists a continuous map $\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}: \mathcal{Q} \rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ satisfying $\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}} \circ \varphi$. Again applying Lemma D.6, we notice that $\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is Borel measurable.

Importantly, since $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=\operatorname{Marg}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ for all $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{D}$, the model $\left\{\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}(q): q \in\right.$ $\mathcal{Q}\}$ of quotient parameters is identifiable, i.e. $\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right) \neq \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)\right)$ for all $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \neq \operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{\prime}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{\prime}\right)$. Therefore, all conditions of Proposition D. 3 are satisfied for the quotient parameter space $\mathcal{Q}$, which suggests that there exists a Borel measurable function $f: \mathcal{X}^{\infty} \rightarrow \mathcal{Q}$ satisfying for every $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{Q}$,

$$
\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})=f\left(X^{(1: \infty)}\right) \quad \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\right) \text {-a.s.. }
$$

This indicates that $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D}}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ is measurable with respect to the $Q$-completion of $\sigma\left(X^{(1: \infty)}\right)$, where $Q$ is the joint probability measure on $\mathcal{Q} \times \mathcal{X}^{\infty}$ defined similar to (D.1).

Since the prior measure $\Pi$ is absolutely continuous with respect to $\mu \times \lambda$, we have

$$
\Pi\left(\mathcal{R} \cap(\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D})^{c}\right) \leq \Pi\left(\left(\mathcal{A}_{2} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}\right) \cap \mathcal{D}^{c}\right)=0
$$

We therefore neglect the set $\mathcal{R} \cap(\mathcal{R} \cap \mathcal{D})^{c}$ from the prior and posterior measures $\Pi, \Pi_{n}$ and let $\varphi_{\#} \Pi$ and $\varphi_{\#} \Pi_{n}$ denote their pushforward measures from $\mathcal{R}$ to $\mathcal{Q}$. By applying Theorem D.2, we obtain for any $\epsilon>0$,

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty}\left(\varphi_{\#} \Pi_{n}\right)\left(\mathcal{O}_{\epsilon}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)\right)^{c}\right)=0 \quad \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{Q}}\left(\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)\right)^{\infty} \text {-a.s. }
$$

for $\varphi_{\#} \Pi$-almost every true quotient parameter $\operatorname{Perm}_{\mathcal{R}}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)$. Using (D.3) and recalling the definition of $\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\epsilon}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ from (3.3), for any $\epsilon>0$, the above result is equivalent to

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \Pi_{n}\left(\widetilde{\mathcal{O}}_{\epsilon}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)^{c}\right)=0 \quad \mathcal{L}\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)^{\infty} \text {-a.s. }
$$

for $\Pi$-almost every true parameter $\left(\mathbf{A}^{*}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{*}\right)$ in $\mathcal{R}$.

# E Posterior Computation: A Complete Guide 

In this section, we provide a complete guide of posterior computation for our model, including the details of our data augmented Gibbs sampler in Section E.1, its subsampling version in Section E.2, and the essentials of our spectral initialization algorithm in Section E.3. Fo ease of reading, we defer a literature overview of subsampling MCMC and related discussions to Section F, and also defer the preliminaries and technical details of our spectral initialization algorithm to Section G.

## E. 1 Data Augmented Gibbs Sampler

To conduct posterior sampling, we have designed a Gibbs sampler using Polya-Gamma data augmentation (Polson et al., 2013). We provide its full details and derivations in this section.

With the model likelihood function specified in Section 2 and the prior distributions specified in Section 4, the joint distribution of $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$ and $\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$ is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right) \\
= & \mathbb{P}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \prod_{n=1}^{N} \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right) \\
= & \mathbb{P}(\boldsymbol{\nu})\left(\prod_{k=1}^{K}\left(\mathbb{P}\left(C_{k}\right) \prod_{1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}} \mathbb{P}\left(\Gamma_{k, i, j}\right)\right)\right)\left(\prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{i=1}^{p_{k}} \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i}\right)\right) \\
& \prod_{n=1}^{N}\left(\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right) \prod_{k=1}^{K} \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right) \\
\propto & \left(\prod_{\mathbf{X}_{0} \in \mathcal{X}_{0}} \nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}}^{\alpha-1}\right) \exp \left(\sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(-\frac{\left(C_{k}-\mu_{C}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{C}^{2}}-\sum_{i=1}^{p_{k-1}} \frac{\left(\Gamma_{k, i, i}-\mu_{\gamma}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{\gamma}^{2}}-\sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k-1}} \frac{\left(\Gamma_{k, i, j}-\mu_{\delta}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{\delta}^{2}}\right)\right) \\
& \left(\prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}} 1_{\Gamma_{k, i, j}>0}\right)\left(\prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{i=1}^{p_{k}} 1_{1 \leq \mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{a}_{k, i} \leq S}\right) \\
& \prod_{n=1}^{N}\left(\nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}} \prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}} \frac{\exp \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}\right)}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}}$ denotes the entry in $\boldsymbol{\nu}$ corresponding to the probability $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right)$.
To obtain conditional conjugacy of parameters, for each $n \in[N], k \in[K],(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$ we introduce an associated augmented variable $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$, conditionally following the distribution

$$
\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k} \sim \operatorname{PG}\left(1, \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)
$$

where PG denotes the Polya-Gamma distribution (Polson et al., 2013) and

$$
\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}:=C_{k}+\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}\right) \mathbf{a}_{k, j}
$$

By properties of the Polya-Gamma distribution, we have the identity

$$
\frac{\exp \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}{1+\exp \left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}=\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{1}{2} \exp \left(\left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\frac{1}{2}\right) \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\frac{\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}}{2}\left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)^{2}\right) \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)} \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right]
$$

where the conditional expectation is taken over $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$. Furthermore, the marginal distribution of each $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$ For each $k \in[K]$, we let

$$
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{k}:=\left\{\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}: n \in[N],(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle\right\}
$$

denote the collection of $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$ 's for all $n, i, j$ and let $\boldsymbol{\omega}:=\left\{\boldsymbol{\omega}_{k}: k \in[K]\right\}$. Letting $g$ denote the density of the Polya-Gamma distribution $\operatorname{PG}(1,0)$, then the density of the Polya-Gamma

distribution $\mathrm{PG}(1, c)$ for $c>0$ is $\propto e^{-\frac{c^{2}}{2} \omega} g(\omega)$. The joint distribution of $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}, \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$ is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}, \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right) \\
= & \mathbb{P}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})\left(\prod_{n=1}^{N} \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)\right)\left(\prod_{n=1}^{N} \prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}} \mathbb{P}\left(\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right)\right) \\
& \propto\left(\prod_{\mathbf{X}_{0} \in \mathcal{X}_{0}} \nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}}^{\alpha-1}\right) \exp \left(\sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(-\frac{\left(C_{k}-\mu_{C}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{C}^{2}}-\sum_{i=1}^{p_{k-1}} \frac{\left(\Gamma_{k, i, i}-\mu_{\gamma}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{\gamma}^{2}}-\sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k-1}} \frac{\left(\Gamma_{k, i, j}-\mu_{\delta}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{\delta}^{2}}\right)\right) \\
& \left(\prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{1 \leq i \leq j \leq p_{k-1}} 1_{\Gamma_{k, i, j}>0}\right)\left(\prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{i=1}^{p_{k}} 1_{1 \leq \mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{a}_{k, i} \leq S}\right) \\
& \left(\prod_{n=1}^{N} \nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}}\right)\left(\prod_{n=1}^{N} \prod_{k=1}^{K} \prod_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}}\left(\exp \left(\left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\frac{1}{2}\right) \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right) \exp \left(-\frac{1}{2} \omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)^{2}\right) g\left(\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

We partition the parameters $\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$, latent variables $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$, and augmented variables $\boldsymbol{\omega}$ into blocks. These blocks include each row $\mathbf{a}_{k, i}$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ for $i \in\left[p_{k}\right], k \in[K]$, the parameter $\boldsymbol{\nu}$, each adjacency matrix $\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}$ for $n \in[N]$, and each entry of all other parameters and variables. The full conditional distributions of each block is given as follows.

For each $k \in[K]$ and each $i \in\left[p_{k}\right]$, letting $\mathbf{A}_{k,-i}:=\left\{\mathbf{a}_{k, j}: j \in\left[p_{k}\right], j \neq i\right\}$ denote the collection of all row vectors in $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ other than $\mathbf{a}_{i, k}$, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{a}_{k, i} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{A}_{k,-i}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k}\right) \propto \prod_{n=1}^{N} \prod_{j=1, j \neq i}^{p_{k}} \frac{\exp \left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}{1+\exp \left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)} 1_{1 \leq \mathbf{1}^{\top} \mathbf{a}_{k, i} \leq S}
$$

which represents a categorical distribution over the space $\mathcal{V}_{k}$ of all $p_{k}$-dimensional binary vectors satisfying our sparsity constraint.

For each $k \in[K]$, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(C_{k} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\omega}_{k}\right) \sim N\left(\widetilde{\mu}_{C_{k}}, \widetilde{\sigma}_{C_{k}}^{2}\right)
$$

which is a normal distribution with mean and variance given by

$$
\begin{gathered}
\widetilde{\mu}_{C_{k}}:=\widetilde{\sigma}_{C_{k}}^{-2}\left(\sigma_{C}^{-2} \mu_{C}+\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}}\left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\frac{1}{2}-\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-C_{k}\right)\right)\right) \\
\widetilde{\sigma}_{C_{k}}^{2}:=\left(\sigma_{C}^{-2}+\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}} \omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

For each $k \in[K], s \in\left\langle p_{k-1}\right\rangle$, letting $\boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k,-(s, t)}:=\boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k} \cap\left\{\Gamma_{k, s, t}\right\}^{c}$ denote the collection of all parameters $C_{k}$ and $\Gamma_{k, i, j}$ 's other than $\Gamma_{k, s, t}$, then we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\Gamma_{k, s, t} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k,-(s, t)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}_{k}\right) \sim N_{+}\left(\widetilde{\mu}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}, \widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}^{2}\right)
$$

which is the normal distribution with mean $\widetilde{\mu}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}$ and variance $\widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}^{2}$ truncated to the positive real line. By denoting $\kappa_{i, j, s, t}^{(n)}:=X_{k-1, s, t}^{(n)}\left(A_{k, i, s} A_{k, j, t}+A_{k, i, t} A_{k, j, s}\right)$, the mean and variance are given by

$$
\begin{gathered}
\widetilde{\mu}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}:=\widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}^{-2}\left(\sigma_{\delta}^{-2} \mu_{\delta}+\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}}\left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\frac{1}{2}-\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\kappa_{i, j, s, t}^{(n)} \Gamma_{k, s, t}\right)\right) \kappa_{i, j, s, t}^{(n)}\right) \\
\widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, t}}^{2}:=\left(\sigma_{\delta}^{-2}+\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}} \omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\left(\kappa_{i, j, s, t}^{(n)}\right)^{2}\right)^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

Similarly, for each $k \in[K], s \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]$, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\Gamma_{k, s, s} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(1: N)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k,-(s, s)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}_{k}\right) \sim N_{+}\left(\widetilde{\mu}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}, \widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}^{2}\right)
$$

which is the normal distribution with mean $\widetilde{\mu}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}$ and variance $\widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}$ truncated to the positive real line. By denoting $\kappa_{i, j, s}:=A_{k, i, s} A_{k, j, s}$, the mean and variance are given by

$$
\begin{gathered}
\widetilde{\mu}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}:=\widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}^{-2}\left(\sigma_{\gamma}^{-2} \mu_{\gamma}+\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}}\left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\frac{1}{2}-\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}-\kappa_{i, j, s} \Gamma_{k, s, s}\right)\right) \kappa_{i, j, s}\right) \\
\widetilde{\sigma}_{\Gamma_{k, s, s}}^{2}:=\left(\sigma_{\gamma}^{-2}+\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k}} \omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \kappa_{i, j, s}\right)^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

For the full conditional distribution of parameter $\boldsymbol{\nu}$, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\nu} \mid \mathbf{X}_{0}^{(1: N)}\right) \sim \operatorname{Dir}(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})
$$

which is a Dirichlet distribution over the probability simplex $\mathcal{S}^{2 \mid \mathcal{X}_{0} \mid-1}$. Its parameter is defined entrywise by

$$
\widetilde{\alpha}_{\mathbf{X}_{0}}:=\alpha+\sum_{n=1}^{N} 1_{\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}=\mathbf{X}_{0}}
$$

for all $\mathbf{X}_{0} \in \mathcal{X}_{0}$, with the entry $\widetilde{\alpha}_{\mathbf{X}_{0}}$ in $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}$ corresponding to the entry $\nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}}$ in $\boldsymbol{\nu}$.
For each $n \in[N], k \in[K],(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, the full conditional distribution of $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$ is by its definition the Polya-Gamma distribution

$$
\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{A}_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k} \sim \operatorname{PG}\left(1, \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)
$$

As for the conditional distributions for blocks of $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$, we partially collapse the augmented variables $\boldsymbol{\omega}$ and compute directly from the joint distribution of $\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}, \mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$. For $k=0$ and each $n \in[N]$, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{1}^{(n)}, \boldsymbol{\nu}, \mathbf{A}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{1}\right) \propto \nu_{\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}} \prod_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{1}} \frac{\exp \left(X_{1, i, j}^{(n)} \psi_{1, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}{1+\exp \left(\psi_{1, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}
$$

which is a categorical distribution over the space of all $p_{0} \times p_{0}$ adjacency matrices $\mathcal{X}_{0}$.
For each $k \in[K-1], n \in[N],(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle$, letting $\mathbf{X}_{k,-(i, j)}^{(n)}:=\mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)} \cap\left\{X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right\}^{c}$ denote the collection of all entries in $\mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)}$ other than $X_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$, we have

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathbb{P}\left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{X}_{k,-(i, j)}^{(n)}, \mathbf{X}_{k+1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{A}_{k:(k+1)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k:(k+1)}\right) \\
\propto \frac{\exp \left(X_{k, i, j}^{(n)} \psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}{1+\exp \left(\psi_{k, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}\left(\prod_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{k+1}} \frac{\exp \left(X_{k+1, i, j}^{(n)} \psi_{k+1, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}{1+\exp \left(\psi_{k+1, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}\right)
\end{gathered}
$$

which is a Bernoulli distribution over $\{0,1\}$. If we instead view the adjacency matrix $\mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)}$ as a whole block, then its conditional distribution is

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{X}_{k-1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{X}_{k+1}^{(n)}, \mathbf{A}_{k:(k+1)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}_{k:(k+1)}\right) \propto \prod_{\ell \in\{k, k+1\}} \prod_{1 \leq i<j \leq p_{\ell}} \frac{\exp \left(X_{\ell, i, j}^{(n)} \psi_{\ell, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}{1+\exp \left(\psi_{\ell, i, j}^{(n)}\right)}
$$

which is a categorical distribution over the space of all $p_{k} \times p_{k}$ adjacency matrices $\mathcal{X}_{k}$.

# E. 2 Subsampling Gibbs Sampler 

As the sample size $N$ and the dimension $p$ get larger, the Gibbs sampler often experiences a high computational burden. The main computational bottlenecks come from sampling the latent adjacency matrices $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$ and the connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$, both of which have linear complexity on the sample size $N$. The sampling of $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$ can be accelerated by drawing the latent $\mathbf{X}^{(1)}, \ldots, \mathbf{X}^{(N)}$ in parallel, due to their conditional independence. To boost the scalability in sampling the parameters $\mathbf{A}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$, it is worth considering whether there is a more efficient alternative way to evaluate their full conditional distributions. A commonly used approach is subsampling MCMC, in which we aim at reducing the complexity of likelihood evaluation by designing a computationally efficient surrogate likelihood function (Quiroz et al., 2018a,c). See Section F. 1 for an overview of related literature. We next adapt this idea to our Gibbs sampler.

After data augmentation, the latent variables of our model include $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$ and $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{(1: N)}$, where $\boldsymbol{\omega}^{(n)}:=\left\{\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}: k \in[K],(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle\right\}$ denotes the collection of augmented variables associated with sample $n$. At each iteration of our subsampling Gibbs sampler, we start by drawing $\mathbf{X}^{(n)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}^{(n)}$ in parallel across $n$ from their standard full conditional distributions. We then uniformly sample without replacement a subset $\mathcal{B}$ of fixed cardinality $|\mathcal{B}|$ from the index set $[N]$. Using this subset of data and latent variables, we obtain an estimator for the data augmented log-likelihood

$$
\widehat{\ell}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}):=\frac{N}{|\mathcal{B}|} \sum_{n \in \mathcal{B}} \log \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}^{(n)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)
$$

With this estimator $\widehat{\ell}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$, we could derive the approximate full conditional distributions of $\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}$ and sample them in blocks in the same way as our standard Gibbs sampler.

As a type of approximate MCMC algorithm (Johndrow et al., 2015; Johndrow and Mattingly, 2017b), the stationary distribution of the subsampling Gibbs sampler is different from the standard Gibbs sampler. For the subset ratio of $\frac{|\mathcal{B}|}{N}=1 \%$, we numerically verify this distance to be small through simulation study in Section H. Our posterior computation involves iterations of the subsampling Gibbs sampler followed by iterations of the standard Gibbs sampler. The subsampling Gibbs samples facilitate fast convergence to the posterior mode after initialization, while posterior inference is conducted based on the standard Gibbs samples. See Section F. 2 for further discussions.

# E. 3 Spectral Initialization 

We now present an additional technique for accelerating posterior computation. The Degree Corrected Mixed Membership (DCMM) model (Jin et al., 2023) is proposed to detect communities in a single sparse network, allowing mixed membership and node degree heterogeneity. In the following, we establish a somewhat surprising link between the DCMM and our model. Using a multilayer hierarchical extension of their Mixed-Score algorithm, we can efficiently find a spectral initialization of our connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$ and significantly reduce the burn-in period needed in our MCMC sampler.

For a single network with $p$ nodes and $q$ communities, DCMM models adjacency matrix $\mathbf{Y}$ as

$$
\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbf{D}, \boldsymbol{\Pi}, \mathbf{Z}]=\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}
$$

where $\mathbf{D} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times p}$ is a positive diagonal matrix, $\boldsymbol{\Pi} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times q}$ has each row $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{i}$ in the simplex $\mathcal{S}^{q-1}$, and $\mathbf{Z}$ is a symmetric positive matrix. Each diagonal entry $D_{i}$ of $\mathbf{D}$ denotes the degree of node $i$, each row $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{i}$ in $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ denotes the mixed membership of node $i$, and each entry $Z_{s, t}$ in $\mathbf{Z}$ represents the adjacency probability of two nodes with partial memberships in communities $s$ and $t$. We find that any two consecutive layers in our model are related to the DCMM in a sense stated in the following theorem. For notational simplicity, we denote $G_{k}:=\max _{i, j \in\left\langle p_{k}\right\rangle} \mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} \mathbf{a}_{k, j}$ for each $k \in[K]$.
Theorem E.1. Let parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$. For each $k \in[K]$ and any $\beta, \epsilon>0$, with probability at least $1-\epsilon$ we have

$$
\left\|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)}-\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}\right\|_{2} \leq p_{k} \sup _{0 \leq x \leq G_{k}}\left|\frac{\exp \left(C_{k}+x\right)}{1+\exp \left(C_{k}+x\right)}-\beta x\right|+\frac{\sqrt{2 p_{k}} \log \left(2 p_{k} \epsilon^{-1}\right)}{\sqrt{N}}
$$

where we let $\mathbf{D}:=\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k} \mathbf{1}\right), \boldsymbol{\Pi}:=\mathbf{D}^{-1} \mathbf{A}_{k}$, and $\mathbf{Z}:=\beta \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k} * \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}_{k-1} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]$.
In Theorem E.1, we have upper bounded the difference between the sample average $\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)}$ and $\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}$ by the sum of a constant term and a term decaying with $N$. In practice, the constant term has smaller magnitude compared to the eigenvalues of $\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbf{X}_{k}^{(n)}$. The Mixed-SCORE algorithm (Jin et al., 2023) is an efficient and accurate spectral method for recovering $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ from $\mathbf{Y}$ in the DCMM, so we can also leverage it to initialize our connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$.

In our multilayer extension of Mixed-SCORE algorithm, we will recover the connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$ in a bottom-up fashion, starting from $\mathbf{A}_{K}$ of the observed layer. By applying the Mixed-SCORE algorithm to $\frac{1}{N} \mathbf{X}_{K}^{(n)}$, we obtain an estimate of $\boldsymbol{\Pi}:=\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{A}_{K} \mathbf{1}\right)^{-1} \mathbf{A}_{K}$ and truncate it into an estimate of $\mathbf{A}_{K}$ through $A_{K, i, j}=1_{\Pi_{i, j} \geq S^{-1}}$. We then pick the $p_{K-1}$ rows in $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ closest to the $p_{K-1}$ vertices of simplex $\mathcal{S}^{p_{K-1}-1}$ and select the adjacency sub-matrices $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{K-1}^{(1: N)}$ by keeping only these $p_{k-1}$ rows and columns of $\mathbf{X}_{K}^{(1: N)}$. By repeatedly applying this approach to $\widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{K-1}^{(1: N)}, \widetilde{\mathbf{X}}_{K-2}^{(1: N)}$, ., we sequentially obtain initial estimates of $\mathbf{A}_{K-1}, \mathbf{A}_{K-2}, \ldots$, which together form the spectral initialization of our connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$. We defer the details of this algorithm to Section G, along with a thorough overview of the DCMM and the proof of Theorem E.1.

## F Subsampling Gibbs Sampler

In this section, we provide a brief overview of subsampling MCMC methods in Section F. 1 and discuss some further variants of our subsampling Gibbs sampler in Section F.2.

# F. 1 Brief Overview of Subsampling MCMC 

Many different versions of subsampling MCMC algorithms have been proposed in the past decade. As a crucial step in any MCMC algorithm, the evaluation of model likelihood often has very high computational complexity when the sample size of data is large. To speed up the MCMC algorithm, we could approximate the model log-likelihood with an estimator based on only a subset of data. For MCMC algorithms based on stochastic differential equations, the approximated versions include stochastic gradient Langevin dynamics (Welling and Teh, 2011) and other variants (Ahn et al., 2012; Ma et al., 2015; Baker et al., 2019). For Metropolis-Hastings algorithms that involve likelihoods in computation of acceptance ratios, efficient estimators for the acceptance ratio based on a subset of data are available (Korattikara et al., 2014; Bardenet et al., 2014, 2017). To reduce the variance of the log-likelihood estimator, different control variate methods (Quiroz et al., 2018a,b) and subsample weighting methods (Maire et al., 2019) have also been proposed.

Despite the numerous subsampling MCMC algorithm, it is important to note that all of them fall into the category of approximate MCMC methods, which do not exactly sample from the target distribution. Theoretical tools have been developed to bound the distance between the stationary distribution of approximate MCMC method and the target distribution when the original MCMC method is uniformly ergodic (Johndrow et al., 2015; Johndrow and Mattingly, 2017a) or geometrically ergodic (Pillai and Smith, 2014; Johndrow and Mattingly, 2017b; Rudolf and Schweizer, 2018; Negrea and Rosenthal, 2021).

## F. 2 Discussions of Subsampling Gibbs Sampler

We now discuss a few possible variants of our subsampling Gibbs sampler.
In the current subsampling Gibbs sampler, while a subset of samples $\mathcal{B}$ is randomly selected at the start of each iteration, all the augmented variables $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$ 's are drawn from their full conditional distributions. These augmented variables can be sampled in parallel efficiently, but the computational complexity will be high when parallel computing is not available. As a compromise, we could instead draw only the subset of augmented variables $\omega_{k, i, j}^{(n)}$ with $n \in \mathcal{B}$. While the resulting Markov chain has a stationary distribution that is theoretically further from the desired posterior distribution, the difference is observed to be small in practice.

As discussed in Section E.2, in each iteration of the subsampling Gibbs sampler, we are estimating the data augmented model log-likelihood using a subset $\mathcal{B}$ of data as

$$
\widehat{\ell}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}):=\frac{N}{|\mathcal{B}|} \sum_{n \in \mathcal{B}} \log \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}^{(n)}, \boldsymbol{\omega}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right)
$$

Other surrogate functions of the log-likelihood could potentially also be designed, in order to further reduce the evaluation time or improve the approximation quality. In current literature (Quiroz et al., 2018c), there are ideas of designing surrogate functions based on Taylor expansions or clustering of the data. We leave this for future work.

## G Spectral Initialization

In this section, we provide the necessary background for the DCMM model and the Mixed-SCORE algorithm (Jin et al., 2023) in Section G.1. We then present the multi-layer extension of MixedSCORE algorithm to our model in Section G.2, which can be used as the spectral initialization. The proof of Theorem E. 1 is provided in Section G.3.

# G. 1 Preliminaries of DCMM and Mixed-SCORE Algorithm 

The Degree Corrected Mixed Membership (DCMM) model (Jin et al., 2023) is designed to detect communities in a single sparse network, allowing mixed membership and node degree heterogeneity. An elementary introduction to the DCMM model and the Mixed-SCORE algorithm is provided here. We refer readers to Jin et al. (2023) for a complete study.

For a single sparse network with a $p \times p$ adjacency matrix $\mathbf{Y}$ and $\widetilde{p}$ communities, the DCMM model assumes that the upper-triangular entries of $\mathbf{Y}$ are conditionally independent given Bernoulli parameters:

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(Y_{i, j}=1 \mid \mathbf{D}, \boldsymbol{\Pi}, \mathbf{Z}\right)=D_{i} D_{j} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{i}^{\top} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{j}
$$

where $D_{i}>0$ denotes the degree of node $i, \boldsymbol{\pi}_{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{\widetilde{p} \times 1}$ denotes the mixed membership vector of node $i$, and $\mathbf{Z} \in \mathbb{R}^{\widetilde{p} \times \widetilde{p}}$ is a symmetric matrix with positive entries. The diagonal matrix $\mathbf{D}=$ $\operatorname{diag}\left(D_{1}, \ldots, D_{p}\right)$, the $p \times \widetilde{p}$ membership matrix $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ with its $i$ th row being $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{i}$, and the matrix $\mathbf{Z}$ together compose the parameters of the DCMM model. Intuitively, the entry $Z_{i, j}(i, j \in[1, \widetilde{p}])$ of $\mathbf{Z}$ models the probability of connection between a node purely belonging to community $i$ and a node purely belonging to community $j$, as in stochastic block models (Holland et al., 1983). Each row vector $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{i}$ in the mixed membership matrix $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ belongs to the probability simplex, with all entries non-negative and summing up to one. Therefore, the probability of connection between two nodes is a weighted average of $Z_{i, j}$ 's over all pairs of communities $(i, j)$ 's that the two nodes partially belong to. Different nodes may have different propensity of being connected to other nodes regardless of their community memberships, which is known as the degree heterogeneity issue. The degree correction matrix $\mathbf{D}$ is introduced to adjust for such degree heterogeneity. In matrix form, we have

$$
\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbf{D}, \boldsymbol{\Pi}, \mathbf{Z}]=\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}
$$

Given the observation $\mathbf{Y}$, the Mixed-SCORE algorithm estimates $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ in three steps: spectral clustering on ratios-of-eigenvectors (SCORE), vertex hunting, and membership reconstruction.

1. In the SCORE step, for the top $\widetilde{p}$ eigenvectors $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{\xi}_{\widetilde{p}}$ of $\mathbf{Y}$, we divide $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{\xi}_{\widetilde{p}}$ entrywise over $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}$ and stack the resulted $\widetilde{p}-1$ vectors by columns into a matrix $\mathbf{R} \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times \widetilde{p}-1}$. For intuition purposes, we also consider the matrix $\widetilde{\mathbf{R}}$ obtained by applying this SCORE step to $\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbf{D}, \boldsymbol{\Pi}, \mathbf{Z}]$ instead of $\mathbf{Y}$, since the difference between $\mathbf{R}$ and $\widetilde{\mathbf{R}}$ is proven to be small. It is also shown that the rows of $\widetilde{\mathbf{R}}$ form a simplex in $\mathbb{R}^{\widetilde{p}-1}$. When each community possesses at least one pure node (a node that belongs purely to this community), the vertices of this simplex corresponds to the rows in $\widetilde{\mathbf{R}}$ of the pure nodes.
2. In the vertex hunting step, we identify the vertices of this simplex using existing methods such as successive projection (Araújo et al., 2001; Nascimento and Dias, 2005). This allows us to find out the pure nodes of the model. To improve the robustness of this step, it is often helpful to conduct $k$-means clustering of the rows in $\mathbf{R}$ before finding the vertices, know as sketched vertex search (SVS, Jin et al., 2023).
3. In the membership reconstruction step, given the pure nodes, the mixed memberships of each node can be recovered through solving linear equation systems.

The mixed memberships $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ can be exactly recovered when the Mixed-SCORE algorithm is applied to $\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbf{D}, \boldsymbol{\Pi}, \mathbf{Z}]$. In practice, only $\mathbf{Y}$ is known and the Mixed-SCORE algorithm is applied to $\mathbf{Y}$, but the estimator of $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$ obtained remains valid and consistent since the difference $\|\mathbf{Y}-\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{Y} \mid \mathbf{D}, \boldsymbol{\Pi}, \mathbf{Z}]\|_{2}$ can be bounded to be small.

# Algorithm 1 Multilayer Mixed-SCORE Algorithm 

Compute the sample mean of observed adjacency matrices

$$
\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{K}:=\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbf{X}_{K}^{(n)}
$$

for $k=K, K-1, \ldots, 1$ do
Apply Mixed-SCORE algorithm to $\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{k}$ and obtain the mixed membership matrix $\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}$;
Truncate $\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}$ to connection matrix $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ entrywise as

$$
A_{k, i, j}:=1_{\Pi_{k, i, j} \geq S^{-1}}, \quad \forall i \in\left[p_{k}\right], j \in\left[p_{k-1}\right]
$$

Find the $p_{k-1}$ rows $\mathcal{I}_{k}$ in $\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}$ closest to distinct pure nodes through

$$
\mathcal{I}_{k}=\underset{\mathcal{I}_{k} \subset\left[p_{k}\right],\left|\mathcal{I}_{k}\right|=p_{k-1}}{\operatorname{argmin}}\left\|\left(\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}\right)_{\mathcal{I}_{k},:}-\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}}\right\|_{F}^{2}
$$

Keep only the $\mathcal{I}_{k}$ rows and $\mathcal{I}_{k}$ columns of $\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{k}$ and let the $p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}$ submatrix be

$$
\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{k-1}:=\left(\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{k}\right)_{\mathcal{I}_{k}, \mathcal{I}_{k}}
$$

end for
Output the initialized connection matrices $\mathbf{A}:=\left\{\mathbf{A}_{k}\right\}_{k=1}^{K}$.

## G. 2 Our Spectral Initialization Algorithm

Theorem E. 1 shows that the sample average of adjacency matrices $\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \overline{\mathbf{x}}_{1}^{(n)}$ is close to the expected adjacency matrix $\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}$ in a DCMM model, with the mixed membership matrix being $\boldsymbol{\Pi}=\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{A}_{1} \mathbf{1}\right)^{-1} \mathbf{A}_{1}$. Given $\boldsymbol{\Pi}$, we can recover the connection matrix $\mathbf{A}_{1}$ through the simple truncation $\mathbf{A}_{1, i, j}=1_{\Pi_{i, j} \geq S^{-1}}$. This suggests an algorithm for warmly initializing $\mathbf{A}$ for $K=1$.

When our Bayesian network has more than two layers (i.e. $K>1$ ), we can take the following approach to iteratively apply the above algorithm for $K=1$ and initialize the connection matrices $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ for $k=K, K-1, \ldots, 1$ in a bottom-up fashion. For each $k \in[K]$, after initializing the connection matrix $\mathbf{A}_{k}$, we can compute the corresponding DCMM mixed membership matrix $\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}=$ $\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{A}_{k} \mathbf{1}\right)^{-1} \mathbf{A}_{k}$. We pick the submatrix of $\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}$ that is closest to an identity matrix, such that these selected $p_{k-1}$ rows in $\boldsymbol{\Pi}_{k}$ roughly corresponds to $p_{k-1}$ distinct pure nodes. We keep only these $p_{k-1}$ rows and columns of the adjacency matrices $\mathbf{X}_{k}^{(1: N)}$, leading to the $p_{k-1} \times p_{k-1}$ adjacency sub-matrices $\overline{\mathbf{X}}_{k}^{(1: N)}$. The obtained adjacency sub-matrices will closely characterize the adjacency between the nodes in the $(k-1)$ th layer in the Bayesian network, to which the Mixed-SCORE algorithm and truncation can be applied again to initialize $\mathbf{A}_{k-1}$. Repeated application of this approach for $k=K, K-1, \ldots, 1$ allows us to initialize all connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$. We refer to this warm initialization algorithm as the Multilayer Mixed-SCORE algorithm and formalize it in Algorithm 1.

# G. 3 Proof of Theorem E. 1 

In the following, we first state the matrix Bernstein inequality. A proof can be found in Theorem 6.1 of Tropp (2015). As before, we let $\|\cdot\|_{2}$ denote the spectral norm of a matrix.

Theorem G. 1 (Matrix Bernstein Inequality). Let $\boldsymbol{Z}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{Z}_{N}$ be independent $d_{1} \times d_{2}$ random matrices satisfying $\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{Z}_{n}\right]=0$ and $\left\|\boldsymbol{Z}_{n}\right\|_{2} \leq L^{\prime}$ almost surely for some constant $L^{\prime}$ and each $n \in[N]$. Then for all $t \geq 0$,

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\left\|\sum_{n=1}^{N} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n}\right\|_{2} \geq t\right) \leq\left(d_{1}+d_{2}\right) \exp \left(-\frac{t^{2} / 2}{L+L^{\prime} t / 3}\right)
$$

where constant $L:=\max \left\{\left\|\sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{Z}_{n} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n}^{\top}\right]\right\|_{2},\left\|\sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{Z}_{n}^{\top} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n}\right]\right\|_{2}\right\}$.
We now prove Theorem E. 1 using Theorem G.1.
Proof of Theorem E.1. We note that it suffices to prove Theorem E. 1 for $K=1$. Under $K=1$, let $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N)}$ be independent realizations from our model with parameter $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}) \in \mathcal{A}_{0} \times \mathcal{T}_{0}$. Conditioned on $\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(1: N)}$, for each entry $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle$ we have $X_{1, i, j}^{(n)}$ independently following the Bernoulli distribution with

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(X_{1, i, j}^{(n)}=1 \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}, \mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}\right)=\mathbb{E}\left[X_{1, i, j}^{(n)}=1 \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}, \mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}\right]=\frac{\exp \left(C+\mathbf{a}_{1, i}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)} * \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{1, j}\right)}{1+\exp \left(C+\mathbf{a}_{1, i}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)} * \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{1, j}\right)}
$$

By noticing

$$
0 \leq \mathbf{a}_{1, i}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)} * \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}\right) \mathbf{a}_{1, j} \leq G=\max _{1 \leq i, j \leq p_{1}} \mathbf{a}_{1, i}^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1} \mathbf{a}_{1, j} \quad \forall(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle, n \in[N]
$$

we have

$$
\left\|\mathbb{E}\left[X_{1, i, j}^{(n)}=1 \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}, \mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}\right]-\beta \mathbf{A}_{1}^{\top}\left(\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)} * \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}\right) \mathbf{A}_{1}\right\|_{2} \leq p_{1} \sup _{0 \leq x \leq G}\left|\frac{\exp (C+x)}{1+\exp (C+x)}-\beta x\right|
$$

which by Jensen's inequality gives

$$
\left\|\mathbb{E}\left[X_{1, i, j}^{(n)}=1 \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]-\beta \mathbf{A}_{1}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1} * \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right]\right) \mathbf{A}_{1}\right\|_{2} \leq p_{1} \sup _{0 \leq x \leq G}\left|\frac{\exp (C+x)}{1+\exp (C+x)}-\beta x\right|
$$

where $\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right]$ is the $p_{0} \times p_{0}$ matrix denoting the expectation of $\mathbf{X}_{0}^{(n)}$ under the categorical distribution over its space $\mathcal{X}_{0}$ parameterized by $\boldsymbol{\nu}$.

For each index pair $(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle$ and sample $n \in[N]$, we define the random matrix

$$
\boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}:=\left(X_{1, i, j}^{(n)}-\mathbb{E}\left[X_{1, i, j}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]\right) \mathbf{E}_{i, j}
$$

where $\mathbf{E}_{i, j}:=\mathbf{e}_{i} \mathbf{e}_{j}^{\top}+\mathbf{e}_{j} \mathbf{e}_{i}^{\top} 1_{i \neq j}$ denotes the indicator matrix with all entries zero except for entries $(i, j)$ and $(j, i)$. We notice that each $\boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}$ satisfies

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]=0, \quad\left\|\boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}\right\|_{2} \leq 1
$$

Furthermore, we have $\mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}^{\top} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]=\mathbb{V}\left[X_{1, i, j} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]\left(\mathbf{E}_{i, i}+\mathbf{E}_{j, j}\right)$ and $\mathbb{V}\left[X_{1, i, j} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right] \leq 1$, which together imply that

$$
\left\|\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle} \mathbb{E}\left[\boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}^{\top}\right]\right\|_{2} \leq N\left\|\sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle}\left(\mathbf{E}_{i, i}+\mathbf{E}_{j, j}\right)\right\|_{2}=N\left(p_{1}-1\right)
$$

By applying the matrix Bernstein inequality in Theorem G. 1 to the summation $\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}$, we obtain for any $t>0$

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\left\|\sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}\right\|_{2} \geq t\right) \leq 2 p_{1} \exp \left(-\frac{t^{2} / 2}{N\left(p_{1}-1\right)+t / 3}\right)
$$

We recall that the DCMM model parameters corresponding to our model are $\mathbf{D}:=\operatorname{diag}\left(\mathbf{A}_{1} \mathbf{1}\right), \boldsymbol{\Pi}:=$ $\mathbf{D}^{-1} \mathbf{A}_{1}, \mathbf{Z}:=\beta \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1} * \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right]$. Since the diagonal entries of adjacency matrices are fixed, by triangle inequality we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{(n)}-\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}\right\|_{2} \leq & \left\|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}_{1}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}\right]-\beta \mathbf{A}_{1}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1} * \mathbb{E}\left[\mathbf{X}_{0} \mid \boldsymbol{\nu}\right]\right) \mathbf{A}_{1}\right\|_{2} \\
& +\left\|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{(i, j) \in\left\langle p_{1}\right\rangle} \boldsymbol{Z}_{n, i, j}\right\|_{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Let $\epsilon>0$ be arbitrary. Putting everything together and letting $t:=\sqrt{2 p_{1} N} \log \left(2 p_{1} \epsilon^{-1}\right)$, with probability at least $1-\epsilon$ we have

$$
\left\|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{N} \mathbf{X}_{1}^{(n)}-\mathbf{D} \boldsymbol{\Pi} \mathbf{Z} \boldsymbol{\Pi}^{\top} \mathbf{D}\right\|_{2} \leq p_{1} \sup _{0 \leq x \leq G}\left|\frac{\exp (C+x)}{1+\exp (C+x)}-\beta x\right|+\frac{\sqrt{2 p_{1}} \log \left(2 p_{1} \epsilon^{-1}\right)}{\sqrt{N}}
$$

# H Simulation Study 

In this section, we numerically evaluate our model consistency and posterior computation approaches through a simulated example. We present the main results in Section H. 1 and additional results with discussions in Section H. 2 .

## H. 1 Main Results

To prepare for the application to brain connectomics, we design our simulation to mimic the sample size and the dimension of the brain connectome data. Let there be $N=1000$ samples of $68 \times 68$ observed adjacency matrix $\mathbf{X}_{K}^{(1: N)}$, generated from our model with the Bayesian network structure of $(K+1)=3$ layers and $p_{0}=4, p_{1}=16, p_{2}=68$ nodes. In the data generating distribution, the continuous parameters of our model have true values specified as $\boldsymbol{\nu}=2^{-p_{0}\left(p_{0}-1\right) / 2} \mathbf{1}, C_{k}=-7$, and $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}=4 \mathbf{1 1}^{\top}+6 \mathbf{I}$, for all $k \in[K]$. The true value of each connection matrix $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ takes the form $\left(\mathbf{I}_{p_{k-1}} \mathbf{M}_{k} \mathbf{B}_{k}\right)^{\top}$ for submatrices $\mathbf{M}_{k} \in \mathcal{M}_{p_{k-1}}$ and $\mathbf{B}_{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{p_{k-1} \times\left(p_{k}-2 p_{k-1}\right)}$ (the exact value is given in Section H.2), with each row $\mathbf{a}_{k, i}^{\top}$ of $\mathbf{A}_{k}$ containing one or two entries of " 1 ". In this way, we have

$\mathbf{A} \in \mathcal{A}_{2} \cap \mathcal{A}_{1}^{c}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Theta} \in \mathcal{T}_{0}$, implying that $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ satisfies the condition for generic identifiability in Theorem 3.7 but not the condition for strict identifiability in Theorem 3.4. We illustrate through this design that generic identifiability suffices for practical purposes. Additionally, the sparsity constraint under $S=2$ holds for each $\mathbf{A}_{k}$.

We impose a prior distribution $\mathbb{P}(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ in the factorized form (4.1), with each independent block of parameters following a weakly informative prior. We let the prior of each $\mathbf{a}_{k, i}$ be uniform over its space $\mathcal{V}_{k}$ and the prior of $\boldsymbol{\nu}$ be uniform over the probability simplex $\mathcal{S}_{+}^{\frac{p_{0}\left(p_{0}-1\right)}{2}-1}$. For the continuous parameters $C$ and $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}$, we follow Gelman (2006) and adopt the weakly informative prior proportional to the standard normal distribution $N(0, \mathbf{I})$, such that each $C_{k} \sim N(0,1)$ and each entry $\Gamma_{k, i, j} \sim N_{+}(0,1)$.

We treat the number of nodes $p_{k}$ in each layer of the Bayesian network and the model parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ as unknown. To determine $p_{k}$, we conduct model selection based on the Watanabe-Akaike information criterion (WAIC) in Watanabe and Opper (2010). Given fixed choices of $p_{k}$, we can then infer model parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ using the posterior computation approaches in Section 4. Specifically, we consider all choices of $p_{k}$ satisfying $p_{k} \geq 2 p_{k-1}$ for each $k \in[K]$, which is necessary for both the strict and generic notions of identifiability. We further focus on $p_{0} \in[2,6]$ for better interpretability of the Bayesian network and also to prevent the parameter $\boldsymbol{\nu}$ from being too highdimensional. For every such choice of $p_{k}$, we use the spectral initialization approach in Section E. 3 to initialize connection matrices $\mathbf{A}$, then run the subsampling Gibbs sampler in Section E. 2 with a $1 \%$ subset ratio for 10,000 iterations, and follow by running the standard Gibbs sampler in Section E. 2 for 100 iterations. The 10,000 iterations of the subsampling Gibbs sampler is used for quick convergence from the spectral initialization, whereas the 100 iterations of the standard Gibbs sampler are used for posterior inference. We use the Gelman-Rubin statistic (Gelman and Rubin, 1992) and the Geweke statistic (Geweke, 1992) for convergence diagnosis of both the subsampling and the standard Gibbs samplers. Detailed results reported in Section H. 2 provide evidence that the Markov chains of Gibbs samplers under each choice of $p_{k}$ have converged.

Given a Bayesian network structure specified by $p_{k}$, at the $t$ th iteration of the standard Gibbs sampler, we have the posterior sample of parameters $\left(\mathbf{A}^{(t)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)}\right)$ and latent variables $\mathbf{X}^{(1: N ; t)}$. Conditioned on the sampled parameters and latent variables, we denote the log likelihood of each observed adjacency matrix $\mathbf{X}_{K}^{(n)}$ as $\ell(t, n):=\log \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{X}_{K}^{(n)} \mid \mathbf{A}^{(t)}, \boldsymbol{\Theta}^{(t)}, \mathbf{X}_{K-1}^{(n ; t)}\right)$. As recommended by Gelman et al. (2014) and Merkle et al. (2019), we use the following formula for computing WAIC

$$
\text { WAIC }:=-2\left(\text { Ippd }-p_{\text {WAIC }}\right)=-2 \sum_{n=1}^{N} \log \left(\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} e^{\ell(t, n)}\right)+2 \sum_{n=1}^{N} \operatorname{var}_{t=1}^{T}(\ell(t, n))
$$

where Ippd stands for the log pointwise predictive density and $p_{\text {WAIC }}$ is an approximation to the effective number of parameters, with $\operatorname{var}_{t=1}^{T}(\ell(t, n))$ denoting the sample variance of $\{\ell(t, n)\}_{t=1}^{T}$. Among all choices of $p_{k}$, we find that WAIC is minimized at their true values $p_{0}=4, p_{1}=16, p_{2}=68$ and changes smoothly as we vary $p_{k}$. This suggests that we are able to select the best model through the WAIC criterion. A heatmap of WAIC with respect to $p_{0}$ and $p_{1}$ is provided in Section H. 2 for further illustration.

For the selected model with Bayesian network structure $p_{0}=4, p_{1}=16, p_{2}=68$, we examine the posterior distribution of model parameters $(\mathbf{A}, \boldsymbol{\Theta})$ under both the subsampling Gibbs sampler and the standard Gibbs sampler. Trace plots of the Hamming distance $\left\|\mathbf{A}-\mathbf{A}^{*}\right\|$ between sample $\mathbf{A}$ and its true value $\mathbf{A}^{*}$, the parameter $C_{2}$, and the entry $\Gamma_{2,1,1}$ of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{2}$ are provided in Figure 7. We observe that the spectral initialization gives a reasonably close estimate of the connection matrix A, with only 7 out of 1152 entries being incorrect. The initialization of continuous parameters

In the 10,000 iterations of the subsampling Gibbs sampler, the parameters quickly converge towards their stationary distributions within the first 2,000 iterations and fluctuate for the next 8,000 iterations, exhibiting good mixing properties. In the following 100 Gibbs sampler iterations, the parameters further converge to their new stationary distributions, which are the desired posterior distributions of parameters. Despite the small subset ratio of $\frac{|B|}{N}=1 \%$ in the subsampling Gibbs sampler, it has stationary distributions very close to the standard Gibbs sampler. All the simulation results have justified (a) our posterior computation framework that combines spectral initialization, subsampling Gibbs sampler, and standard Gibbs sampler; and also (b) our model selection approach based on the WAIC criterion. We note that based on our preliminary simulations, the presented results from one trial are typical and similar to observations from repeated experiments and different data generating distributions. Therefore, we will be adopting the same computational framework in the following real data section when analyzing the brain connectome data, where no true values of model structure or model parameters are known.

with the trace plot of the Hamming distance between samples of $\mathbf{A}$ and the true $\mathbf{A}$ shown in Figure 7 of the main paper.

For the continuous parameters $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ at each layer $k$, we plot their true values and their posterior means under both Gibbs samplers in Figure 12. Both subsampling Gibbs sampler and standard Gibbs sampler produce samples that are close to the true values of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{2}$. While the subsampling Gibbs sampler tends to underestimate some parameters in the first layer and overestimate some parameters in the second layer, the samples from the standard Gibbs sampler have demonstrated to estimate the true values of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}$ consistently. The posterior estimates of the continuous parameters $C_{1}, C_{2}$ are also found to demonstrate similar behaviors. This agrees with the trace plots of $C_{k}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{k}$ shown in Figure 7 of the main paper.

As discussed in Section E. 2 of the main paper, the stationary distribution of standard Gibbs sampler is the true posterior distribution, whereas the stationary distribution of subsampling Gibbs sampler only approximates the true posterior distribution. We now numerically compare the error of this approximation in $W_{1}$-distance and justify the use of our subsampling Gibbs sampler. For any two probability measures $\mu, \nu$ on a Polish space $\mathcal{Z}$, the Wasserstein 1-distance between them is defined as $W_{1}(\mu, \nu):=\inf _{\pi \in \Gamma(\mu, \nu)} \int_{\mathcal{Z} \times \mathcal{Z}}\|x-y\|_{1} \mathrm{~d} \pi(x, y)$, where $\Gamma(\mu, \nu)$ denotes the collection of all couplings of $\mu, \nu$. For each entry of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{2}$, we compute the $W_{1}$-distance between the empirical distributions of posterior samples under subsampling and standard Gibbs samplers. We present the ratio of $W_{1}$-distance over the true value for each entry in Figure 13. We find for each entry of $\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{2}$ that the $W_{1}$ approximation error of the stationary distribution for subsampling Gibbs sampler is relatively small compared to the scale of the true value. This is also consistent with our observations from Figure 7 of the main paper.
